8/// \file
9/// This transformation implements the well known scalar replacement of
10/// aggregates transformation. It tries to identify promotable elements of an
11/// aggregate alloca, and promote them to registers. It will also try to
12/// convert uses of an element (or set of elements) of an alloca into a vector
13/// or bitfield-style integer scalar if appropriate.
14///
15/// It works to do this with minimal slicing of the alloca so that regions
16/// which are merely transferred in and out of external memory remain unchanged
17/// and are not decomposed to scalar code.
18///
19/// Because this also performs alloca promotion, it can be thought of as also
20/// serving the purpose of SSA formation. The algorithm iterates on the
21/// function until all opportunities for promotion have been realized.
22///
23//===----------------------------------------------------------------------===//

153/// A used slice of an alloca.
154///
155/// This structure represents a slice of an alloca used by some instruction. It
156/// stores both the begin and end offsets of this use, a pointer to the use
157/// itself, and a flag indicating whether we can classify the use as splittable
158/// or not when forming partitions of the alloca.
159class Slice {
160 /// The beginning offset of the range.
161 uint64_t BeginOffset = 0;
162
163 /// The ending offset, not included in the range.
164 uint64_t EndOffset = 0;
165
166 /// Storage for both the use of this slice and whether it can be
167 /// split.
168 PointerIntPair<Use *, 1, bool> UseAndIsSplittable;
169
170public:
171 Slice() = default;
172
173 Slice(uint64_t BeginOffset, uint64_t EndOffset, Use *U, bool IsSplittable)
174 : BeginOffset(BeginOffset), EndOffset(EndOffset),
175 UseAndIsSplittable(U, IsSplittable) {}
176
177 uint64_t beginOffset() const { return BeginOffset; }
178 uint64_t endOffset() const { return EndOffset; }
179
180 bool isSplittable() const { return UseAndIsSplittable.getInt(); }
181 void makeUnsplittable() { UseAndIsSplittable.setInt(false); }
182
183 Use *getUse() const { return UseAndIsSplittable.getPointer(); }
184
185 bool isDead() const { return getUse() == nullptr; }
186 void kill() { UseAndIsSplittable.setPointer(nullptr); }
187
188 /// Support for ordering ranges.
189 ///
190 /// This provides an ordering over ranges such that start offsets are
191 /// always increasing, and within equal start offsets, the end offsets are
192 /// decreasing. Thus the spanning range comes first in a cluster with the
193 /// same start position.
194 bool operator<(const Slice &RHS) const {
195 if (beginOffset() < RHS.beginOffset())
196 return true;
197 if (beginOffset() > RHS.beginOffset())
198 return false;
199 if (isSplittable() != RHS.isSplittable())
200 return !isSplittable();
201 if (endOffset() > RHS.endOffset())
202 return true;
203 return false;
204 }
205
206 /// Support comparison with a single offset to allow binary searches.
207 friend LLVM_ATTRIBUTE_UNUSED bool operator<(const Slice &LHS,
208 uint64_t RHSOffset) {
209 return LHS.beginOffset() < RHSOffset;
210 }
211 friend LLVM_ATTRIBUTE_UNUSED bool operator<(uint64_t LHSOffset,
212 const Slice &RHS) {
213 return LHSOffset < RHS.beginOffset();
214 }
215
216 bool operator==(const Slice &RHS) const {
217 return isSplittable() == RHS.isSplittable() &&
218 beginOffset() == RHS.beginOffset() && endOffset() == RHS.endOffset();
219 }
220 bool operator!=(const Slice &RHS) const { return !operator==(RHS); }
221};
222
223} // end anonymous namespace

225/// Representation of the alloca slices.
226///
227/// This class represents the slices of an alloca which are formed by its
228/// various uses. If a pointer escapes, we can't fully build a representation
229/// for the slices used and we reflect that in this structure. The uses are
230/// stored, sorted by increasing beginning offset and with unsplittable slices
231/// starting at a particular offset before splittable slices.
232class llvm::sroa::AllocaSlices {
233public:
234 /// Construct the slices of a particular alloca.
235 AllocaSlices(const DataLayout &DL, AllocaInst &AI);
236
237 /// Test whether a pointer to the allocation escapes our analysis.
238 ///
239 /// If this is true, the slices are never fully built and should be
240 /// ignored.
241 bool isEscaped() const { return PointerEscapingInstr; }
242
243 /// Support for iterating over the slices.
244 /// @{
245 using iterator = SmallVectorImpl<Slice>::iterator;
246 using range = iterator_range<iterator>;
247
248 iterator begin() { return Slices.begin(); }
249 iterator end() { return Slices.end(); }
250
251 using const_iterator = SmallVectorImpl<Slice>::const_iterator;
252 using const_range = iterator_range<const_iterator>;
253
254 const_iterator begin() const { return Slices.begin(); }
255 const_iterator end() const { return Slices.end(); }
256 /// @}
257
258 /// Erase a range of slices.
259 void erase(iterator Start, iterator Stop) { Slices.erase(Start, Stop); }
260
261 /// Insert new slices for this alloca.
262 ///
263 /// This moves the slices into the alloca's slices collection, and re-sorts
264 /// everything so that the usual ordering properties of the alloca's slices
265 /// hold.
266 void insert(ArrayRef<Slice> NewSlices) {
267 int OldSize = Slices.size();
268 Slices.append(NewSlices.begin(), NewSlices.end());
269 auto SliceI = Slices.begin() + OldSize;
270 llvm::sort(SliceI, Slices.end());
271 std::inplace_merge(Slices.begin(), SliceI, Slices.end());
272 }
273
274 // Forward declare the iterator and range accessor for walking the
275 // partitions.
276 class partition_iterator;
277 iterator_range<partition_iterator> partitions();
278
279 /// Access the dead users for this alloca.
280 ArrayRef<Instruction *> getDeadUsers() const { return DeadUsers; }
281
282 /// Access the dead operands referring to this alloca.
283 ///
284 /// These are operands which have cannot actually be used to refer to the
285 /// alloca as they are outside its range and the user doesn't correct for
286 /// that. These mostly consist of PHI node inputs and the like which we just
287 /// need to replace with undef.
288 ArrayRef<Use *> getDeadOperands() const { return DeadOperands; }
289
290#if !defined(NDEBUG) || defined(LLVM_ENABLE_DUMP)
291 void print(raw_ostream &OS, const_iterator I, StringRef Indent = " ") const;
292 void printSlice(raw_ostream &OS, const_iterator I,
293 StringRef Indent = " ") const;
294 void printUse(raw_ostream &OS, const_iterator I,
295 StringRef Indent = " ") const;
296 void print(raw_ostream &OS) const;
297 void dump(const_iterator I) const;
298 void dump() const;
299#endif

301private:
302 template <typename DerivedT, typename RetT = void> class BuilderBase;
303 class SliceBuilder;
304
305 friend class AllocaSlices::SliceBuilder;

309 AllocaInst &AI;

312 /// The instruction responsible for this alloca not having a known set
313 /// of slices.
314 ///
315 /// When an instruction (potentially) escapes the pointer to the alloca, we
316 /// store a pointer to that here and abort trying to form slices of the
317 /// alloca. This will be null if the alloca slices are analyzed successfully.
318 Instruction *PointerEscapingInstr;
319
320 /// The slices of the alloca.
321 ///
322 /// We store a vector of the slices formed by uses of the alloca here. This
323 /// vector is sorted by increasing begin offset, and then the unsplittable
324 /// slices before the splittable ones. See the Slice inner class for more
325 /// details.
326 SmallVector<Slice, 8> Slices;
327
328 /// Instructions which will become dead if we rewrite the alloca.
329 ///
330 /// Note that these are not separated by slice. This is because we expect an
331 /// alloca to be completely rewritten or not rewritten at all. If rewritten,
332 /// all these instructions can simply be removed and replaced with undef as
333 /// they come from outside of the allocated space.
334 SmallVector<Instruction *, 8> DeadUsers;
335
336 /// Operands which will become dead if we rewrite the alloca.
337 ///
338 /// These are operands that in their particular use can be replaced with
339 /// undef when we rewrite the alloca. These show up in out-of-bounds inputs
340 /// to PHI nodes and the like. They aren't entirely dead (there might be
341 /// a GEP back into the bounds using it elsewhere) and nor is the PHI, but we
342 /// want to swap this particular input for undef to simplify the use lists of
343 /// the alloca.
344 SmallVector<Use *, 8> DeadOperands;
345};

347/// A partition of the slices.
348///
349/// An ephemeral representation for a range of slices which can be viewed as
350/// a partition of the alloca. This range represents a span of the alloca's
351/// memory which cannot be split, and provides access to all of the slices
352/// overlapping some part of the partition.
353///
354/// Objects of this type are produced by traversing the alloca's slices, but
355/// are only ephemeral and not persistent.
356class llvm::sroa::Partition {
357private:
358 friend class AllocaSlices;
359 friend class AllocaSlices::partition_iterator;
360
361 using iterator = AllocaSlices::iterator;
362
363 /// The beginning and ending offsets of the alloca for this
364 /// partition.
365 uint64_t BeginOffset, EndOffset;
366
367 /// The start and end iterators of this partition.
368 iterator SI, SJ;
369
370 /// A collection of split slice tails overlapping the partition.
371 SmallVector<Slice *, 4> SplitTails;
372
373 /// Raw constructor builds an empty partition starting and ending at
374 /// the given iterator.
375 Partition(iterator SI) : SI(SI), SJ(SI) {}
376
377public:
378 /// The start offset of this partition.
379 ///
380 /// All of the contained slices start at or after this offset.
381 uint64_t beginOffset() const { return BeginOffset; }
382
383 /// The end offset of this partition.
384 ///
385 /// All of the contained slices end at or before this offset.
386 uint64_t endOffset() const { return EndOffset; }
387
388 /// The size of the partition.
389 ///
390 /// Note that this can never be zero.
391 uint64_t size() const {
392 assert(BeginOffset < EndOffset && "Partitions must span some bytes!");
393 return EndOffset - BeginOffset;
394 }
395
396 /// Test whether this partition contains no slices, and merely spans
397 /// a region occupied by split slices.
398 bool empty() const { return SI == SJ; }
399
400 /// \name Iterate slices that start within the partition.
401 /// These may be splittable or unsplittable. They have a begin offset >= the
402 /// partition begin offset.
403 /// @{
404 // FIXME: We should probably define a "concat_iterator" helper and use that
405 // to stitch together pointee_iterators over the split tails and the
406 // contiguous iterators of the partition. That would give a much nicer
407 // interface here. We could then additionally expose filtered iterators for
408 // split, unsplit, and unsplittable splices based on the usage patterns.
409 iterator begin() const { return SI; }
410 iterator end() const { return SJ; }
411 /// @}
412
413 /// Get the sequence of split slice tails.
414 ///
415 /// These tails are of slices which start before this partition but are
416 /// split and overlap into the partition. We accumulate these while forming
417 /// partitions.
418 ArrayRef<Slice *> splitSliceTails() const { return SplitTails; }
419};
420
421/// An iterator over partitions of the alloca's slices.
422///
423/// This iterator implements the core algorithm for partitioning the alloca's
424/// slices. It is a forward iterator as we don't support backtracking for
425/// efficiency reasons, and re-use a single storage area to maintain the
426/// current set of split slices.
427///
428/// It is templated on the slice iterator type to use so that it can operate
429/// with either const or non-const slice iterators.
430class AllocaSlices::partition_iterator
431 : public iterator_facade_base<partition_iterator, std::forward_iterator_tag,
432 Partition> {
433 friend class AllocaSlices;
434
435 /// Most of the state for walking the partitions is held in a class
436 /// with a nice interface for examining them.
437 Partition P;
438
439 /// We need to keep the end of the slices to know when to stop.
440 AllocaSlices::iterator SE;
441
442 /// We also need to keep track of the maximum split end offset seen.
443 /// FIXME: Do we really?
444 uint64_t MaxSplitSliceEndOffset = 0;
445
446 /// Sets the partition to be empty at given iterator, and sets the
447 /// end iterator.
448 partition_iterator(AllocaSlices::iterator SI, AllocaSlices::iterator SE)
449 : P(SI), SE(SE) {
450 // If not already at the end, advance our state to form the initial
451 // partition.
452 if (SI != SE)
453 advance();
454 }
455
456 /// Advance the iterator to the next partition.
457 ///
458 /// Requires that the iterator not be at the end of the slices.
459 void advance() {
460 assert((P.SI != SE || !P.SplitTails.empty()) &&
461 "Cannot advance past the end of the slices!");
462
463 // Clear out any split uses which have ended.
464 if (!P.SplitTails.empty()) {
465 if (P.EndOffset >= MaxSplitSliceEndOffset) {
466 // If we've finished all splits, this is easy.
467 P.SplitTails.clear();
468 MaxSplitSliceEndOffset = 0;
469 } else {
470 // Remove the uses which have ended in the prior partition. This
471 // cannot change the max split slice end because we just checked that
472 // the prior partition ended prior to that max.
473 P.SplitTails.erase(llvm::remove_if(P.SplitTails,
474 [&](Slice *S) {
475 return S->endOffset() <=
476 P.EndOffset;
477 }),
478 P.SplitTails.end());
479 assert(llvm::any_of(P.SplitTails,
480 [&](Slice *S) {
481 return S->endOffset() == MaxSplitSliceEndOffset;
482 }) &&
483 "Could not find the current max split slice offset!");
484 assert(llvm::all_of(P.SplitTails,
485 [&](Slice *S) {
486 return S->endOffset() <= MaxSplitSliceEndOffset;
487 }) &&
488 "Max split slice end offset is not actually the max!");
489 }
490 }
491
492 // If P.SI is already at the end, then we've cleared the split tail and
493 // now have an end iterator.
494 if (P.SI == SE) {
495 assert(P.SplitTails.empty() && "Failed to clear the split slices!");
496 return;
497 }
498
499 // If we had a non-empty partition previously, set up the state for
500 // subsequent partitions.
501 if (P.SI != P.SJ) {
502 // Accumulate all the splittable slices which started in the old
503 // partition into the split list.
504 for (Slice &S : P)
505 if (S.isSplittable() && S.endOffset() > P.EndOffset) {
506 P.SplitTails.push_back(&S);
507 MaxSplitSliceEndOffset =
508 std::max(S.endOffset(), MaxSplitSliceEndOffset);
509 }
510
511 // Start from the end of the previous partition.
512 P.SI = P.SJ;
513
514 // If P.SI is now at the end, we at most have a tail of split slices.
515 if (P.SI == SE) {
516 P.BeginOffset = P.EndOffset;
517 P.EndOffset = MaxSplitSliceEndOffset;
518 return;
519 }
520
521 // If the we have split slices and the next slice is after a gap and is
522 // not splittable immediately form an empty partition for the split
523 // slices up until the next slice begins.
524 if (!P.SplitTails.empty() && P.SI->beginOffset() != P.EndOffset &&
525 !P.SI->isSplittable()) {
526 P.BeginOffset = P.EndOffset;
527 P.EndOffset = P.SI->beginOffset();
528 return;
529 }
530 }
531
532 // OK, we need to consume new slices. Set the end offset based on the
533 // current slice, and step SJ past it. The beginning offset of the
534 // partition is the beginning offset of the next slice unless we have
535 // pre-existing split slices that are continuing, in which case we begin
536 // at the prior end offset.
537 P.BeginOffset = P.SplitTails.empty() ? P.SI->beginOffset() : P.EndOffset;
538 P.EndOffset = P.SI->endOffset();
539 ++P.SJ;
540
541 // There are two strategies to form a partition based on whether the
542 // partition starts with an unsplittable slice or a splittable slice.
543 if (!P.SI->isSplittable()) {
544 // When we're forming an unsplittable region, it must always start at
545 // the first slice and will extend through its end.
546 assert(P.BeginOffset == P.SI->beginOffset());
547
548 // Form a partition including all of the overlapping slices with this
549 // unsplittable slice.
550 while (P.SJ != SE && P.SJ->beginOffset() < P.EndOffset) {
551 if (!P.SJ->isSplittable())
552 P.EndOffset = std::max(P.EndOffset, P.SJ->endOffset());
553 ++P.SJ;
554 }
555
556 // We have a partition across a set of overlapping unsplittable
557 // partitions.
558 return;
559 }
560
561 // If we're starting with a splittable slice, then we need to form
562 // a synthetic partition spanning it and any other overlapping splittable
563 // splices.
564 assert(P.SI->isSplittable() && "Forming a splittable partition!");
565
566 // Collect all of the overlapping splittable slices.
567 while (P.SJ != SE && P.SJ->beginOffset() < P.EndOffset &&
568 P.SJ->isSplittable()) {
569 P.EndOffset = std::max(P.EndOffset, P.SJ->endOffset());
570 ++P.SJ;
571 }
572
573 // Back upiP.EndOffset if we ended the span early when encountering an
574 // unsplittable slice. This synthesizes the early end offset of
575 // a partition spanning only splittable slices.
576 if (P.SJ != SE && P.SJ->beginOffset() < P.EndOffset) {
577 assert(!P.SJ->isSplittable());
578 P.EndOffset = P.SJ->beginOffset();
579 }
580 }
581
582public:
583 bool operator==(const partition_iterator &RHS) const {
584 assert(SE == RHS.SE &&
585 "End iterators don't match between compared partition iterators!");
586
587 // The observed positions of partitions is marked by the P.SI iterator and
588 // the emptiness of the split slices. The latter is only relevant when
589 // P.SI == SE, as the end iterator will additionally have an empty split
590 // slices list, but the prior may have the same P.SI and a tail of split
591 // slices.
592 if (P.SI == RHS.P.SI && P.SplitTails.empty() == RHS.P.SplitTails.empty()) {
593 assert(P.SJ == RHS.P.SJ &&
594 "Same set of slices formed two different sized partitions!");
595 assert(P.SplitTails.size() == RHS.P.SplitTails.size() &&
596 "Same slice position with differently sized non-empty split "
597 "slice tails!");
598 return true;
599 }
600 return false;
601 }
602
603 partition_iterator &operator++() {
604 advance();
605 return *this;
606 }
607
608 Partition &operator*() { return P; }
609};
610
611/// A forward range over the partitions of the alloca's slices.
612///
613/// This accesses an iterator range over the partitions of the alloca's
614/// slices. It computes these partitions on the fly based on the overlapping
615/// offsets of the slices and the ability to split them. It will visit "empty"
616/// partitions to cover regions of the alloca only accessed via split
617/// slices.
618iterator_range<AllocaSlices::partition_iterator> AllocaSlices::partitions() {
619 return make_range(partition_iterator(begin(), end()),
620 partition_iterator(end(), end()));
621}

623static Value *foldSelectInst(SelectInst &SI) {
624 // If the condition being selected on is a constant or the same value is
625 // being selected between, fold the select. Yes this does (rarely) happen
626 // early on.
627 if (ConstantInt *CI = dyn_cast<ConstantInt>(SI.getCondition()))
628 return SI.getOperand(1 + CI->isZero());
629 if (SI.getOperand(1) == SI.getOperand(2))
630 return SI.getOperand(1);
631
632 return nullptr;
633}
634
635/// A helper that folds a PHI node or a select.
636static Value *foldPHINodeOrSelectInst(Instruction &I) {
637 if (PHINode *PN = dyn_cast<PHINode>(&I)) {
638 // If PN merges together the same value, return that value.
639 return PN->hasConstantValue();
640 }
641 return foldSelectInst(cast<SelectInst>(I));
642}

644/// Builder for the alloca slices.
645///
646/// This class builds a set of alloca slices by recursively visiting the uses
647/// of an alloca and making a slice for each load and store at each offset.
648class AllocaSlices::SliceBuilder : public PtrUseVisitor<SliceBuilder> {
649 friend class PtrUseVisitor<SliceBuilder>;
650 friend class InstVisitor<SliceBuilder>;
651
652 using Base = PtrUseVisitor<SliceBuilder>;
653
654 const uint64_t AllocSize;
655 AllocaSlices &AS;
656
657 SmallDenseMap<Instruction *, unsigned> MemTransferSliceMap;
658 SmallDenseMap<Instruction *, uint64_t> PHIOrSelectSizes;
659
660 /// Set to de-duplicate dead instructions found in the use walk.
661 SmallPtrSet<Instruction *, 4> VisitedDeadInsts;
662
663public:
664 SliceBuilder(const DataLayout &DL, AllocaInst &AI, AllocaSlices &AS)
665 : PtrUseVisitor<SliceBuilder>(DL),
666 AllocSize(DL.getTypeAllocSize(AI.getAllocatedType())), AS(AS) {}
667
668private:
669 void markAsDead(Instruction &I) {
670 if (VisitedDeadInsts.insert(&I).second)
671 AS.DeadUsers.push_back(&I);
672 }
673
674 void insertUse(Instruction &I, const APInt &Offset, uint64_t Size,
675 bool IsSplittable = false) {
676 // Completely skip uses which have a zero size or start either before or
677 // past the end of the allocation.
678 if (Size == 0 || Offset.uge(AllocSize)) {
679 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << "WARNING: Ignoring " << Size << " byte use @"
680 << Offset
681 << " which has zero size or starts outside of the "
682 << AllocSize << " byte alloca:\n"
683 << " alloca: " << AS.AI << "\n"
684 << " use: " << I << "\n");
685 return markAsDead(I);
686 }
687
688 uint64_t BeginOffset = Offset.getZExtValue();
689 uint64_t EndOffset = BeginOffset + Size;
690
691 // Clamp the end offset to the end of the allocation. Note that this is
692 // formulated to handle even the case where "BeginOffset + Size" overflows.
693 // This may appear superficially to be something we could ignore entirely,
694 // but that is not so! There may be widened loads or PHI-node uses where
695 // some instructions are dead but not others. We can't completely ignore
696 // them, and so have to record at least the information here.
697 assert(AllocSize >= BeginOffset); // Established above.
698 if (Size > AllocSize - BeginOffset) {
699 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << "WARNING: Clamping a " << Size << " byte use @"
700 << Offset << " to remain within the " << AllocSize
701 << " byte alloca:\n"
702 << " alloca: " << AS.AI << "\n"
703 << " use: " << I << "\n");
704 EndOffset = AllocSize;
705 }
706
707 AS.Slices.push_back(Slice(BeginOffset, EndOffset, U, IsSplittable));
708 }
709
710 void visitBitCastInst(BitCastInst &BC) {
711 if (BC.use_empty())
712 return markAsDead(BC);
713
714 return Base::visitBitCastInst(BC);
715 }
716
717 void visitGetElementPtrInst(GetElementPtrInst &GEPI) {
718 if (GEPI.use_empty())
719 return markAsDead(GEPI);
720
721 if (SROAStrictInbounds && GEPI.isInBounds()) {
722 // FIXME: This is a manually un-factored variant of the basic code inside
723 // of GEPs with checking of the inbounds invariant specified in the
724 // langref in a very strict sense. If we ever want to enable
725 // SROAStrictInbounds, this code should be factored cleanly into
726 // PtrUseVisitor, but it is easier to experiment with SROAStrictInbounds
727 // by writing out the code here where we have the underlying allocation
728 // size readily available.
729 APInt GEPOffset = Offset;
730 const DataLayout &DL = GEPI.getModule()->getDataLayout();
731 for (gep_type_iterator GTI = gep_type_begin(GEPI),
732 GTE = gep_type_end(GEPI);
733 GTI != GTE; ++GTI) {
734 ConstantInt *OpC = dyn_cast<ConstantInt>(GTI.getOperand());
735 if (!OpC)
736 break;
737
738 // Handle a struct index, which adds its field offset to the pointer.
739 if (StructType *STy = GTI.getStructTypeOrNull()) {
740 unsigned ElementIdx = OpC->getZExtValue();
741 const StructLayout *SL = DL.getStructLayout(STy);
742 GEPOffset +=
743 APInt(Offset.getBitWidth(), SL->getElementOffset(ElementIdx));
744 } else {
745 // For array or vector indices, scale the index by the size of the
746 // type.
747 APInt Index = OpC->getValue().sextOrTrunc(Offset.getBitWidth());
748 GEPOffset += Index * APInt(Offset.getBitWidth(),
749 DL.getTypeAllocSize(GTI.getIndexedType()));
750 }
751
752 // If this index has computed an intermediate pointer which is not
753 // inbounds, then the result of the GEP is a poison value and we can
754 // delete it and all uses.
755 if (GEPOffset.ugt(AllocSize))
756 return markAsDead(GEPI);
757 }
758 }
759
760 return Base::visitGetElementPtrInst(GEPI);
761 }
762
763 void handleLoadOrStore(Type *Ty, Instruction &I, const APInt &Offset,
764 uint64_t Size, bool IsVolatile) {
765 // We allow splitting of non-volatile loads and stores where the type is an
766 // integer type. These may be used to implement 'memcpy' or other "transfer
767 // of bits" patterns.
768 bool IsSplittable = Ty->isIntegerTy() && !IsVolatile;
769
770 insertUse(I, Offset, Size, IsSplittable);
771 }
772
773 void visitLoadInst(LoadInst &LI) {
774 assert((!LI.isSimple() || LI.getType()->isSingleValueType()) &&
775 "All simple FCA loads should have been pre-split");
776
777 if (!IsOffsetKnown)
778 return PI.setAborted(&LI);
779
780 const DataLayout &DL = LI.getModule()->getDataLayout();
781 uint64_t Size = DL.getTypeStoreSize(LI.getType());
782 return handleLoadOrStore(LI.getType(), LI, Offset, Size, LI.isVolatile());
783 }
784
785 void visitStoreInst(StoreInst &SI) {
786 Value *ValOp = SI.getValueOperand();
787 if (ValOp == *U)
788 return PI.setEscapedAndAborted(&SI);
789 if (!IsOffsetKnown)
790 return PI.setAborted(&SI);
791
792 const DataLayout &DL = SI.getModule()->getDataLayout();
793 uint64_t Size = DL.getTypeStoreSize(ValOp->getType());
794
795 // If this memory access can be shown to *statically* extend outside the
796 // bounds of the allocation, it's behavior is undefined, so simply
797 // ignore it. Note that this is more strict than the generic clamping
798 // behavior of insertUse. We also try to handle cases which might run the
799 // risk of overflow.
800 // FIXME: We should instead consider the pointer to have escaped if this
801 // function is being instrumented for addressing bugs or race conditions.
802 if (Size > AllocSize || Offset.ugt(AllocSize - Size)) {
803 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << "WARNING: Ignoring " << Size << " byte store @"
804 << Offset << " which extends past the end of the "
805 << AllocSize << " byte alloca:\n"
806 << " alloca: " << AS.AI << "\n"
807 << " use: " << SI << "\n");
808 return markAsDead(SI);
809 }
810
811 assert((!SI.isSimple() || ValOp->getType()->isSingleValueType()) &&
812 "All simple FCA stores should have been pre-split");
813 handleLoadOrStore(ValOp->getType(), SI, Offset, Size, SI.isVolatile());
814 }
815
816 void visitMemSetInst(MemSetInst &II) {
817 assert(II.getRawDest() == *U && "Pointer use is not the destination?");
818 ConstantInt *Length = dyn_cast<ConstantInt>(II.getLength());
819 if ((Length && Length->getValue() == 0) ||
820 (IsOffsetKnown && Offset.uge(AllocSize)))
821 // Zero-length mem transfer intrinsics can be ignored entirely.
822 return markAsDead(II);
823
824 if (!IsOffsetKnown)
825 return PI.setAborted(&II);
826
827 insertUse(II, Offset, Length ? Length->getLimitedValue()
828 : AllocSize - Offset.getLimitedValue(),
829 (bool)Length);
830 }
831
832 void visitMemTransferInst(MemTransferInst &II) {
833 ConstantInt *Length = dyn_cast<ConstantInt>(II.getLength());
834 if (Length && Length->getValue() == 0)
835 // Zero-length mem transfer intrinsics can be ignored entirely.
836 return markAsDead(II);
837
838 // Because we can visit these intrinsics twice, also check to see if the
839 // first time marked this instruction as dead. If so, skip it.
840 if (VisitedDeadInsts.count(&II))
841 return;
842
843 if (!IsOffsetKnown)
844 return PI.setAborted(&II);
845
846 // This side of the transfer is completely out-of-bounds, and so we can
847 // nuke the entire transfer. However, we also need to nuke the other side
848 // if already added to our partitions.
849 // FIXME: Yet another place we really should bypass this when
850 // instrumenting for ASan.
851 if (Offset.uge(AllocSize)) {
852 SmallDenseMap<Instruction *, unsigned>::iterator MTPI =
853 MemTransferSliceMap.find(&II);
854 if (MTPI != MemTransferSliceMap.end())
855 AS.Slices[MTPI->second].kill();
856 return markAsDead(II);
857 }
858
859 uint64_t RawOffset = Offset.getLimitedValue();
860 uint64_t Size = Length ? Length->getLimitedValue() : AllocSize - RawOffset;
861
862 // Check for the special case where the same exact value is used for both
863 // source and dest.
864 if (*U == II.getRawDest() && *U == II.getRawSource()) {
865 // For non-volatile transfers this is a no-op.
866 if (!II.isVolatile())
867 return markAsDead(II);
868
869 return insertUse(II, Offset, Size, /*IsSplittable=*/false);
870 }
871
872 // If we have seen both source and destination for a mem transfer, then
873 // they both point to the same alloca.
874 bool Inserted;
875 SmallDenseMap<Instruction *, unsigned>::iterator MTPI;
876 std::tie(MTPI, Inserted) =
877 MemTransferSliceMap.insert(std::make_pair(&II, AS.Slices.size()));
878 unsigned PrevIdx = MTPI->second;
879 if (!Inserted) {
880 Slice &PrevP = AS.Slices[PrevIdx];
881
882 // Check if the begin offsets match and this is a non-volatile transfer.
883 // In that case, we can completely elide the transfer.
884 if (!II.isVolatile() && PrevP.beginOffset() == RawOffset) {
885 PrevP.kill();
886 return markAsDead(II);
887 }
888
889 // Otherwise we have an offset transfer within the same alloca. We can't
890 // split those.
891 PrevP.makeUnsplittable();
892 }
893
894 // Insert the use now that we've fixed up the splittable nature.
895 insertUse(II, Offset, Size, /*IsSplittable=*/Inserted && Length);
896
897 // Check that we ended up with a valid index in the map.
898 assert(AS.Slices[PrevIdx].getUse()->getUser() == &II &&
899 "Map index doesn't point back to a slice with this user.");
900 }
901
902 // Disable SRoA for any intrinsics except for lifetime invariants.
903 // FIXME: What about debug intrinsics? This matches old behavior, but
904 // doesn't make sense.
905 void visitIntrinsicInst(IntrinsicInst &II) {
906 if (!IsOffsetKnown)
907 return PI.setAborted(&II);
908
909 if (II.isLifetimeStartOrEnd()) {
910 ConstantInt *Length = cast<ConstantInt>(II.getArgOperand(0));
911 uint64_t Size = std::min(AllocSize - Offset.getLimitedValue(),
912 Length->getLimitedValue());
913 insertUse(II, Offset, Size, true);
914 return;
915 }
916
917 Base::visitIntrinsicInst(II);
918 }
919
920 Instruction *hasUnsafePHIOrSelectUse(Instruction *Root, uint64_t &Size) {
921 // We consider any PHI or select that results in a direct load or store of
922 // the same offset to be a viable use for slicing purposes. These uses
923 // are considered unsplittable and the size is the maximum loaded or stored
924 // size.
925 SmallPtrSet<Instruction *, 4> Visited;
926 SmallVector<std::pair<Instruction *, Instruction *>, 4> Uses;
927 Visited.insert(Root);
928 Uses.push_back(std::make_pair(cast<Instruction>(*U), Root));
929 const DataLayout &DL = Root->getModule()->getDataLayout();
930 // If there are no loads or stores, the access is dead. We mark that as
931 // a size zero access.
932 Size = 0;
933 do {
934 Instruction *I, *UsedI;
935 std::tie(UsedI, I) = Uses.pop_back_val();
936
937 if (LoadInst *LI = dyn_cast<LoadInst>(I)) {
938 Size = std::max(Size, DL.getTypeStoreSize(LI->getType()));
939 continue;
940 }
941 if (StoreInst *SI = dyn_cast<StoreInst>(I)) {
942 Value *Op = SI->getOperand(0);
943 if (Op == UsedI)
944 return SI;
945 Size = std::max(Size, DL.getTypeStoreSize(Op->getType()));
946 continue;
947 }
948
949 if (GetElementPtrInst *GEP = dyn_cast<GetElementPtrInst>(I)) {
950 if (!GEP->hasAllZeroIndices())
951 return GEP;
952 } else if (!isa<BitCastInst>(I) && !isa<PHINode>(I) &&
953 !isa<SelectInst>(I)) {
954 return I;
955 }
956
957 for (User *U : I->users())
958 if (Visited.insert(cast<Instruction>(U)).second)
959 Uses.push_back(std::make_pair(I, cast<Instruction>(U)));
960 } while (!Uses.empty());
961
962 return nullptr;
963 }
964
965 void visitPHINodeOrSelectInst(Instruction &I) {
966 assert(isa<PHINode>(I) || isa<SelectInst>(I));
967 if (I.use_empty())
968 return markAsDead(I);
969
970 // TODO: We could use SimplifyInstruction here to fold PHINodes and
971 // SelectInsts. However, doing so requires to change the current
972 // dead-operand-tracking mechanism. For instance, suppose neither loading
973 // from %U nor %other traps. Then "load (select undef, %U, %other)" does not
974 // trap either. However, if we simply replace %U with undef using the
975 // current dead-operand-tracking mechanism, "load (select undef, undef,
976 // %other)" may trap because the select may return the first operand
977 // "undef".
978 if (Value *Result = foldPHINodeOrSelectInst(I)) {
979 if (Result == *U)
980 // If the result of the constant fold will be the pointer, recurse
981 // through the PHI/select as if we had RAUW'ed it.
982 enqueueUsers(I);
983 else
984 // Otherwise the operand to the PHI/select is dead, and we can replace
985 // it with undef.
986 AS.DeadOperands.push_back(U);
987
988 return;
989 }
990
991 if (!IsOffsetKnown)
992 return PI.setAborted(&I);
993
994 // See if we already have computed info on this node.
995 uint64_t &Size = PHIOrSelectSizes[&I];
996 if (!Size) {
997 // This is a new PHI/Select, check for an unsafe use of it.
998 if (Instruction *UnsafeI = hasUnsafePHIOrSelectUse(&I, Size))
999 return PI.setAborted(UnsafeI);
1000 }
1001
1002 // For PHI and select operands outside the alloca, we can't nuke the entire
1003 // phi or select -- the other side might still be relevant, so we special
1004 // case them here and use a separate structure to track the operands
1005 // themselves which should be replaced with undef.
1006 // FIXME: This should instead be escaped in the event we're instrumenting
1007 // for address sanitization.
1008 if (Offset.uge(AllocSize)) {
1009 AS.DeadOperands.push_back(U);
1010 return;
1011 }
1012
1013 insertUse(I, Offset, Size);
1014 }
1015
1016 void visitPHINode(PHINode &PN) { visitPHINodeOrSelectInst(PN); }
1017
1018 void visitSelectInst(SelectInst &SI) { visitPHINodeOrSelectInst(SI); }
1019
1020 /// Disable SROA entirely if there are unhandled users of the alloca.
1021 void visitInstruction(Instruction &I) { PI.setAborted(&I); }
1022};

1024AllocaSlices::AllocaSlices(const DataLayout &DL, AllocaInst &AI)
1025 :
1026#if !defined(NDEBUG) || defined(LLVM_ENABLE_DUMP)
1027 AI(AI),
1028#endif
1029 PointerEscapingInstr(nullptr) {
1030 SliceBuilder PB(DL, AI, *this);
1031 SliceBuilder::PtrInfo PtrI = PB.visitPtr(AI);
1032 if (PtrI.isEscaped() || PtrI.isAborted()) {
1033 // FIXME: We should sink the escape vs. abort info into the caller nicely,
1034 // possibly by just storing the PtrInfo in the AllocaSlices.
1035 PointerEscapingInstr = PtrI.getEscapingInst() ? PtrI.getEscapingInst()
1036 : PtrI.getAbortingInst();
1037 assert(PointerEscapingInstr && "Did not track a bad instruction");
1038 return;
1039 }
1040
1041 Slices.erase(
1042 llvm::remove_if(Slices, [](const Slice &S) { return S.isDead(); }),
1043 Slices.end());
1044
1045#ifndef NDEBUG
1046 if (SROARandomShuffleSlices) {
1047 std::mt19937 MT(static_cast<unsigned>(
1048 std::chrono::system_clock::now().time_since_epoch().count()));
1049 llvm::shuffle(Slices.begin(), Slices.end(), MT);
1050 }
1051#endif
1052
1053 // Sort the uses. This arranges for the offsets to be in ascending order,
1054 // and the sizes to be in descending order.
1055 llvm::sort(Slices);
1056}

1099/// Walk the range of a partitioning looking for a common type to cover this
1100/// sequence of slices.
1101static Type *findCommonType(AllocaSlices::const_iterator B,
1102 AllocaSlices::const_iterator E,
1103 uint64_t EndOffset) {
1104 Type *Ty = nullptr;
1105 bool TyIsCommon = true;
1106 IntegerType *ITy = nullptr;
1107
1108 // Note that we need to look at *every* alloca slice's Use to ensure we
1109 // always get consistent results regardless of the order of slices.
1110 for (AllocaSlices::const_iterator I = B; I != E; ++I) {
1111 Use *U = I->getUse();
1112 if (isa<IntrinsicInst>(*U->getUser()))
1113 continue;
1114 if (I->beginOffset() != B->beginOffset() || I->endOffset() != EndOffset)
1115 continue;
1116
1117 Type *UserTy = nullptr;
1118 if (LoadInst *LI = dyn_cast<LoadInst>(U->getUser())) {
1119 UserTy = LI->getType();
1120 } else if (StoreInst *SI = dyn_cast<StoreInst>(U->getUser())) {
1121 UserTy = SI->getValueOperand()->getType();
1122 }
1123
1124 if (IntegerType *UserITy = dyn_cast_or_null<IntegerType>(UserTy)) {
1125 // If the type is larger than the partition, skip it. We only encounter
1126 // this for split integer operations where we want to use the type of the
1127 // entity causing the split. Also skip if the type is not a byte width
1128 // multiple.
1129 if (UserITy->getBitWidth() % 8 != 0 ||
1130 UserITy->getBitWidth() / 8 > (EndOffset - B->beginOffset()))
1131 continue;
1132
1133 // Track the largest bitwidth integer type used in this way in case there
1134 // is no common type.
1135 if (!ITy || ITy->getBitWidth() < UserITy->getBitWidth())
1136 ITy = UserITy;
1137 }
1138
1139 // To avoid depending on the order of slices, Ty and TyIsCommon must not
1140 // depend on types skipped above.
1141 if (!UserTy || (Ty && Ty != UserTy))
1142 TyIsCommon = false; // Give up on anything but an iN type.
1143 else
1144 Ty = UserTy;
1145 }
1146
1147 return TyIsCommon ? Ty : ITy;
1148}
1149
1150/// PHI instructions that use an alloca and are subsequently loaded can be
1151/// rewritten to load both input pointers in the pred blocks and then PHI the
1152/// results, allowing the load of the alloca to be promoted.
1153/// From this:
1154/// %P2 = phi [i32* %Alloca, i32* %Other]
1155/// %V = load i32* %P2
1156/// to:
1157/// %V1 = load i32* %Alloca -> will be mem2reg'd
1158/// ...
1159/// %V2 = load i32* %Other
1160/// ...
1161/// %V = phi [i32 %V1, i32 %V2]
1162///
1163/// We can do this to a select if its only uses are loads and if the operands
1164/// to the select can be loaded unconditionally.
1165///
1166/// FIXME: This should be hoisted into a generic utility, likely in
1167/// Transforms/Util/Local.h
1168static bool isSafePHIToSpeculate(PHINode &PN) {
1169 // For now, we can only do this promotion if the load is in the same block
1170 // as the PHI, and if there are no stores between the phi and load.
1171 // TODO: Allow recursive phi users.
1172 // TODO: Allow stores.
1173 BasicBlock *BB = PN.getParent();
1174 unsigned MaxAlign = 0;
1175 bool HaveLoad = false;
1176 for (User *U : PN.users()) {
1177 LoadInst *LI = dyn_cast<LoadInst>(U);
1178 if (!LI || !LI->isSimple())
1179 return false;
1180
1181 // For now we only allow loads in the same block as the PHI. This is
1182 // a common case that happens when instcombine merges two loads through
1183 // a PHI.
1184 if (LI->getParent() != BB)
1185 return false;
1186
1187 // Ensure that there are no instructions between the PHI and the load that
1188 // could store.
1189 for (BasicBlock::iterator BBI(PN); &*BBI != LI; ++BBI)
1190 if (BBI->mayWriteToMemory())
1191 return false;
1192
1193 MaxAlign = std::max(MaxAlign, LI->getAlignment());
1194 HaveLoad = true;
1195 }
1196
1197 if (!HaveLoad)
1198 return false;
1199
1200 const DataLayout &DL = PN.getModule()->getDataLayout();
1201
1202 // We can only transform this if it is safe to push the loads into the
1203 // predecessor blocks. The only thing to watch out for is that we can't put
1204 // a possibly trapping load in the predecessor if it is a critical edge.
1205 for (unsigned Idx = 0, Num = PN.getNumIncomingValues(); Idx != Num; ++Idx) {
1206 Instruction *TI = PN.getIncomingBlock(Idx)->getTerminator();
1207 Value *InVal = PN.getIncomingValue(Idx);
1208
1209 // If the value is produced by the terminator of the predecessor (an
1210 // invoke) or it has side-effects, there is no valid place to put a load
1211 // in the predecessor.
1212 if (TI == InVal || TI->mayHaveSideEffects())
1213 return false;
1214
1215 // If the predecessor has a single successor, then the edge isn't
1216 // critical.
1217 if (TI->getNumSuccessors() == 1)
1218 continue;
1219
1220 // If this pointer is always safe to load, or if we can prove that there
1221 // is already a load in the block, then we can move the load to the pred
1222 // block.
1223 if (isSafeToLoadUnconditionally(InVal, MaxAlign, DL, TI))
1224 continue;
1225
1226 return false;
1227 }
1228
1229 return true;
1230}
1231
1232static void speculatePHINodeLoads(PHINode &PN) {
1233 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << " original: " << PN << "\n");
1234
1235 LoadInst *SomeLoad = cast<LoadInst>(PN.user_back());
1236 Type *LoadTy = SomeLoad->getType();
1237 IRBuilderTy PHIBuilder(&PN);
1238 PHINode *NewPN = PHIBuilder.CreatePHI(LoadTy, PN.getNumIncomingValues(),
1239 PN.getName() + ".sroa.speculated");
1240
1241 // Get the AA tags and alignment to use from one of the loads. It doesn't
1242 // matter which one we get and if any differ.
1243 AAMDNodes AATags;
1244 SomeLoad->getAAMetadata(AATags);
1245 unsigned Align = SomeLoad->getAlignment();
1246
1247 // Rewrite all loads of the PN to use the new PHI.
1248 while (!PN.use_empty()) {
1249 LoadInst *LI = cast<LoadInst>(PN.user_back());
1250 LI->replaceAllUsesWith(NewPN);
1251 LI->eraseFromParent();
1252 }
1253
1254 // Inject loads into all of the pred blocks.
1255 DenseMap<BasicBlock*, Value*> InjectedLoads;
1256 for (unsigned Idx = 0, Num = PN.getNumIncomingValues(); Idx != Num; ++Idx) {
1257 BasicBlock *Pred = PN.getIncomingBlock(Idx);
1258 Value *InVal = PN.getIncomingValue(Idx);
1259
1260 // A PHI node is allowed to have multiple (duplicated) entries for the same
1261 // basic block, as long as the value is the same. So if we already injected
1262 // a load in the predecessor, then we should reuse the same load for all
1263 // duplicated entries.
1264 if (Value* V = InjectedLoads.lookup(Pred)) {
1265 NewPN->addIncoming(V, Pred);
1266 continue;
1267 }
1268
1269 Instruction *TI = Pred->getTerminator();
1270 IRBuilderTy PredBuilder(TI);
1271
1272 LoadInst *Load = PredBuilder.CreateLoad(
1273 LoadTy, InVal,
1274 (PN.getName() + ".sroa.speculate.load." + Pred->getName()));
1275 ++NumLoadsSpeculated;
1276 Load->setAlignment(Align);
1277 if (AATags)
1278 Load->setAAMetadata(AATags);
1279 NewPN->addIncoming(Load, Pred);
1280 InjectedLoads[Pred] = Load;
1281 }
1282
1283 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << " speculated to: " << *NewPN << "\n");
1284 PN.eraseFromParent();
1285}
1286
1287/// Select instructions that use an alloca and are subsequently loaded can be
1288/// rewritten to load both input pointers and then select between the result,
1289/// allowing the load of the alloca to be promoted.
1290/// From this:
1291/// %P2 = select i1 %cond, i32* %Alloca, i32* %Other
1292/// %V = load i32* %P2
1293/// to:
1294/// %V1 = load i32* %Alloca -> will be mem2reg'd
1295/// %V2 = load i32* %Other
1296/// %V = select i1 %cond, i32 %V1, i32 %V2
1297///
1298/// We can do this to a select if its only uses are loads and if the operand
1299/// to the select can be loaded unconditionally.
1300static bool isSafeSelectToSpeculate(SelectInst &SI) {
1301 Value *TValue = SI.getTrueValue();
1302 Value *FValue = SI.getFalseValue();
1303 const DataLayout &DL = SI.getModule()->getDataLayout();
1304
1305 for (User *U : SI.users()) {
1306 LoadInst *LI = dyn_cast<LoadInst>(U);
1307 if (!LI || !LI->isSimple())
1308 return false;
1309
1310 // Both operands to the select need to be dereferenceable, either
1311 // absolutely (e.g. allocas) or at this point because we can see other
1312 // accesses to it.
1313 if (!isSafeToLoadUnconditionally(TValue, LI->getAlignment(), DL, LI))
1314 return false;
1315 if (!isSafeToLoadUnconditionally(FValue, LI->getAlignment(), DL, LI))
1316 return false;
1317 }
1318
1319 return true;
1320}
1321
1322static void speculateSelectInstLoads(SelectInst &SI) {
1323 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << " original: " << SI << "\n");
1324
1325 IRBuilderTy IRB(&SI);
1326 Value *TV = SI.getTrueValue();
1327 Value *FV = SI.getFalseValue();
1328 // Replace the loads of the select with a select of two loads.
1329 while (!SI.use_empty()) {
1330 LoadInst *LI = cast<LoadInst>(SI.user_back());
1331 assert(LI->isSimple() && "We only speculate simple loads");
1332
1333 IRB.SetInsertPoint(LI);
1334 LoadInst *TL = IRB.CreateLoad(LI->getType(), TV,
1335 LI->getName() + ".sroa.speculate.load.true");
1336 LoadInst *FL = IRB.CreateLoad(LI->getType(), FV,
1337 LI->getName() + ".sroa.speculate.load.false");
1338 NumLoadsSpeculated += 2;
1339
1340 // Transfer alignment and AA info if present.
1341 TL->setAlignment(LI->getAlignment());
1342 FL->setAlignment(LI->getAlignment());
1343
1344 AAMDNodes Tags;
1345 LI->getAAMetadata(Tags);
1346 if (Tags) {
1347 TL->setAAMetadata(Tags);
1348 FL->setAAMetadata(Tags);
1349 }
1350
1351 Value *V = IRB.CreateSelect(SI.getCondition(), TL, FL,
1352 LI->getName() + ".sroa.speculated");
1353
1354 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << " speculated to: " << *V << "\n");
1355 LI->replaceAllUsesWith(V);
1356 LI->eraseFromParent();
1357 }
1358 SI.eraseFromParent();
1359}

1361/// Build a GEP out of a base pointer and indices.
1362///
1363/// This will return the BasePtr if that is valid, or build a new GEP
1364/// instruction using the IRBuilder if GEP-ing is needed.
1365static Value *buildGEP(IRBuilderTy &IRB, Value *BasePtr,
1366 SmallVectorImpl<Value *> &Indices, Twine NamePrefix) {
1367 if (Indices.empty())
1368 return BasePtr;
1369
1370 // A single zero index is a no-op, so check for this and avoid building a GEP
1371 // in that case.
1372 if (Indices.size() == 1 && cast<ConstantInt>(Indices.back())->isZero())
1373 return BasePtr;
1374
1375 return IRB.CreateInBoundsGEP(BasePtr->getType()->getPointerElementType(),
1376 BasePtr, Indices, NamePrefix + "sroa_idx");
1377}
1378
1379/// Get a natural GEP off of the BasePtr walking through Ty toward
1380/// TargetTy without changing the offset of the pointer.
1381///
1382/// This routine assumes we've already established a properly offset GEP with
1383/// Indices, and arrived at the Ty type. The goal is to continue to GEP with
1384/// zero-indices down through type layers until we find one the same as
1385/// TargetTy. If we can't find one with the same type, we at least try to use
1386/// one with the same size. If none of that works, we just produce the GEP as
1387/// indicated by Indices to have the correct offset.
1388static Value *getNaturalGEPWithType(IRBuilderTy &IRB, const DataLayout &DL,
1389 Value *BasePtr, Type *Ty, Type *TargetTy,
1390 SmallVectorImpl<Value *> &Indices,
1391 Twine NamePrefix) {
1392 if (Ty == TargetTy)
1393 return buildGEP(IRB, BasePtr, Indices, NamePrefix);
1394
1395 // Offset size to use for the indices.
1396 unsigned OffsetSize = DL.getIndexTypeSizeInBits(BasePtr->getType());
1397
1398 // See if we can descend into a struct and locate a field with the correct
1399 // type.
1400 unsigned NumLayers = 0;
1401 Type *ElementTy = Ty;
1402 do {
1403 if (ElementTy->isPointerTy())
1404 break;
1405
1406 if (ArrayType *ArrayTy = dyn_cast<ArrayType>(ElementTy)) {
1407 ElementTy = ArrayTy->getElementType();
1408 Indices.push_back(IRB.getIntN(OffsetSize, 0));
1409 } else if (VectorType *VectorTy = dyn_cast<VectorType>(ElementTy)) {
1410 ElementTy = VectorTy->getElementType();
1411 Indices.push_back(IRB.getInt32(0));
1412 } else if (StructType *STy = dyn_cast<StructType>(ElementTy)) {
1413 if (STy->element_begin() == STy->element_end())
1414 break; // Nothing left to descend into.
1415 ElementTy = *STy->element_begin();
1416 Indices.push_back(IRB.getInt32(0));
1417 } else {
1418 break;
1419 }
1420 ++NumLayers;
1421 } while (ElementTy != TargetTy);
1422 if (ElementTy != TargetTy)
1423 Indices.erase(Indices.end() - NumLayers, Indices.end());
1424
1425 return buildGEP(IRB, BasePtr, Indices, NamePrefix);
1426}
1427
1428/// Recursively compute indices for a natural GEP.
1429///
1430/// This is the recursive step for getNaturalGEPWithOffset that walks down the
1431/// element types adding appropriate indices for the GEP.
1432static Value *getNaturalGEPRecursively(IRBuilderTy &IRB, const DataLayout &DL,
1433 Value *Ptr, Type *Ty, APInt &Offset,
1434 Type *TargetTy,
1435 SmallVectorImpl<Value *> &Indices,
1436 Twine NamePrefix) {
1437 if (Offset == 0)
1438 return getNaturalGEPWithType(IRB, DL, Ptr, Ty, TargetTy, Indices,
1439 NamePrefix);
1440
1441 // We can't recurse through pointer types.
1442 if (Ty->isPointerTy())
1443 return nullptr;
1444
1445 // We try to analyze GEPs over vectors here, but note that these GEPs are
1446 // extremely poorly defined currently. The long-term goal is to remove GEPing
1447 // over a vector from the IR completely.
1448 if (VectorType *VecTy = dyn_cast<VectorType>(Ty)) {
1449 unsigned ElementSizeInBits = DL.getTypeSizeInBits(VecTy->getScalarType());
1450 if (ElementSizeInBits % 8 != 0) {
1451 // GEPs over non-multiple of 8 size vector elements are invalid.
1452 return nullptr;
1453 }
1454 APInt ElementSize(Offset.getBitWidth(), ElementSizeInBits / 8);
1455 APInt NumSkippedElements = Offset.sdiv(ElementSize);
1456 if (NumSkippedElements.ugt(VecTy->getNumElements()))
1457 return nullptr;
1458 Offset -= NumSkippedElements * ElementSize;
1459 Indices.push_back(IRB.getInt(NumSkippedElements));
1460 return getNaturalGEPRecursively(IRB, DL, Ptr, VecTy->getElementType(),
1461 Offset, TargetTy, Indices, NamePrefix);
1462 }
1463
1464 if (ArrayType *ArrTy = dyn_cast<ArrayType>(Ty)) {
1465 Type *ElementTy = ArrTy->getElementType();
1466 APInt ElementSize(Offset.getBitWidth(), DL.getTypeAllocSize(ElementTy));
1467 APInt NumSkippedElements = Offset.sdiv(ElementSize);
1468 if (NumSkippedElements.ugt(ArrTy->getNumElements()))
1469 return nullptr;
1470
1471 Offset -= NumSkippedElements * ElementSize;
1472 Indices.push_back(IRB.getInt(NumSkippedElements));
1473 return getNaturalGEPRecursively(IRB, DL, Ptr, ElementTy, Offset, TargetTy,
1474 Indices, NamePrefix);
1475 }
1476
1477 StructType *STy = dyn_cast<StructType>(Ty);
1478 if (!STy)
1479 return nullptr;
1480
1481 const StructLayout *SL = DL.getStructLayout(STy);
1482 uint64_t StructOffset = Offset.getZExtValue();
1483 if (StructOffset >= SL->getSizeInBytes())
1484 return nullptr;
1485 unsigned Index = SL->getElementContainingOffset(StructOffset);
1486 Offset -= APInt(Offset.getBitWidth(), SL->getElementOffset(Index));
1487 Type *ElementTy = STy->getElementType(Index);
1488 if (Offset.uge(DL.getTypeAllocSize(ElementTy)))
1489 return nullptr; // The offset points into alignment padding.
1490
1491 Indices.push_back(IRB.getInt32(Index));
1492 return getNaturalGEPRecursively(IRB, DL, Ptr, ElementTy, Offset, TargetTy,
1493 Indices, NamePrefix);
1494}
1495
1496/// Get a natural GEP from a base pointer to a particular offset and
1497/// resulting in a particular type.
1498///
1499/// The goal is to produce a "natural" looking GEP that works with the existing
1500/// composite types to arrive at the appropriate offset and element type for
1501/// a pointer. TargetTy is the element type the returned GEP should point-to if
1502/// possible. We recurse by decreasing Offset, adding the appropriate index to
1503/// Indices, and setting Ty to the result subtype.
1504///
1505/// If no natural GEP can be constructed, this function returns null.
1506static Value *getNaturalGEPWithOffset(IRBuilderTy &IRB, const DataLayout &DL,
1507 Value *Ptr, APInt Offset, Type *TargetTy,
1508 SmallVectorImpl<Value *> &Indices,
1509 Twine NamePrefix) {
1510 PointerType *Ty = cast<PointerType>(Ptr->getType());
1511
1512 // Don't consider any GEPs through an i8* as natural unless the TargetTy is
1513 // an i8.
1514 if (Ty == IRB.getInt8PtrTy(Ty->getAddressSpace()) && TargetTy->isIntegerTy(8))
1515 return nullptr;
1516
1517 Type *ElementTy = Ty->getElementType();
1518 if (!ElementTy->isSized())
1519 return nullptr; // We can't GEP through an unsized element.
1520 APInt ElementSize(Offset.getBitWidth(), DL.getTypeAllocSize(ElementTy));
1521 if (ElementSize == 0)
1522 return nullptr; // Zero-length arrays can't help us build a natural GEP.
1523 APInt NumSkippedElements = Offset.sdiv(ElementSize);
1524
1525 Offset -= NumSkippedElements * ElementSize;
1526 Indices.push_back(IRB.getInt(NumSkippedElements));
1527 return getNaturalGEPRecursively(IRB, DL, Ptr, ElementTy, Offset, TargetTy,
1528 Indices, NamePrefix);
1529}
1530
1531/// Compute an adjusted pointer from Ptr by Offset bytes where the
1532/// resulting pointer has PointerTy.
1533///
1534/// This tries very hard to compute a "natural" GEP which arrives at the offset
1535/// and produces the pointer type desired. Where it cannot, it will try to use
1536/// the natural GEP to arrive at the offset and bitcast to the type. Where that
1537/// fails, it will try to use an existing i8* and GEP to the byte offset and
1538/// bitcast to the type.
1539///
1540/// The strategy for finding the more natural GEPs is to peel off layers of the
1541/// pointer, walking back through bit casts and GEPs, searching for a base
1542/// pointer from which we can compute a natural GEP with the desired
1543/// properties. The algorithm tries to fold as many constant indices into
1544/// a single GEP as possible, thus making each GEP more independent of the
1545/// surrounding code.
1546static Value *getAdjustedPtr(IRBuilderTy &IRB, const DataLayout &DL, Value *Ptr,
1547 APInt Offset, Type *PointerTy, Twine NamePrefix) {
1548 // Make sure that we're not inadvertently inserting a bitcast between address
1549 // spaces.
1550 unsigned AS = Ptr->getType()->getPointerAddressSpace();
1551 if (PointerTy->getPointerAddressSpace() != AS)
1552 PointerTy = PointerTy->getPointerElementType()->getPointerTo(AS);
1553 // Even though we don't look through PHI nodes, we could be called on an
1554 // instruction in an unreachable block, which may be on a cycle.
1555 SmallPtrSet<Value *, 4> Visited;
1556 Visited.insert(Ptr);
1557 SmallVector<Value *, 4> Indices;
1558
1559 // We may end up computing an offset pointer that has the wrong type. If we
1560 // never are able to compute one directly that has the correct type, we'll
1561 // fall back to it, so keep it and the base it was computed from around here.
1562 Value *OffsetPtr = nullptr;
1563 Value *OffsetBasePtr;
1564
1565 // Remember any i8 pointer we come across to re-use if we need to do a raw
1566 // byte offset.
1567 Value *Int8Ptr = nullptr;
1568 APInt Int8PtrOffset(Offset.getBitWidth(), 0);
1569
1570 Type *TargetTy = PointerTy->getPointerElementType();
1571
1572 do {
1573 // First fold any existing GEPs into the offset.
1574 while (GEPOperator *GEP = dyn_cast<GEPOperator>(Ptr)) {
1575 APInt GEPOffset(Offset.getBitWidth(), 0);
1576 if (!GEP->accumulateConstantOffset(DL, GEPOffset))
1577 break;
1578 Offset += GEPOffset;
1579 Ptr = GEP->getPointerOperand();
1580 if (!Visited.insert(Ptr).second)
1581 break;
1582 }
1583
1584 // See if we can perform a natural GEP here.
1585 Indices.clear();
1586 if (Value *P = getNaturalGEPWithOffset(IRB, DL, Ptr, Offset, TargetTy,
1587 Indices, NamePrefix)) {
1588 // If we have a new natural pointer at the offset, clear out any old
1589 // offset pointer we computed. Unless it is the base pointer or
1590 // a non-instruction, we built a GEP we don't need. Zap it.
1591 if (OffsetPtr && OffsetPtr != OffsetBasePtr)
1592 if (Instruction *I = dyn_cast<Instruction>(OffsetPtr)) {
1593 assert(I->use_empty() && "Built a GEP with uses some how!");
1594 I->eraseFromParent();
1595 }
1596 OffsetPtr = P;
1597 OffsetBasePtr = Ptr;
1598 // If we also found a pointer of the right type, we're done.
1599 if (P->getType() == PointerTy)
1600 return P;
1601 }
1602
1603 // Stash this pointer if we've found an i8*.
1604 if (Ptr->getType()->isIntegerTy(8)) {
1605 Int8Ptr = Ptr;
1606 Int8PtrOffset = Offset;
1607 }
1608
1609 // Peel off a layer of the pointer and update the offset appropriately.
1610 if (Operator::getOpcode(Ptr) == Instruction::BitCast) {
1611 Ptr = cast<Operator>(Ptr)->getOperand(0);
1612 } else if (GlobalAlias *GA = dyn_cast<GlobalAlias>(Ptr)) {
1613 if (GA->isInterposable())
1614 break;
1615 Ptr = GA->getAliasee();
1616 } else {
1617 break;
1618 }
1619 assert(Ptr->getType()->isPointerTy() && "Unexpected operand type!");
1620 } while (Visited.insert(Ptr).second);
1621
1622 if (!OffsetPtr) {
1623 if (!Int8Ptr) {
1624 Int8Ptr = IRB.CreateBitCast(
1625 Ptr, IRB.getInt8PtrTy(PointerTy->getPointerAddressSpace()),
1626 NamePrefix + "sroa_raw_cast");
1627 Int8PtrOffset = Offset;
1628 }
1629
1630 OffsetPtr = Int8PtrOffset == 0
1631 ? Int8Ptr
1632 : IRB.CreateInBoundsGEP(IRB.getInt8Ty(), Int8Ptr,
1633 IRB.getInt(Int8PtrOffset),
1634 NamePrefix + "sroa_raw_idx");
1635 }
1636 Ptr = OffsetPtr;
1637
1638 // On the off chance we were targeting i8*, guard the bitcast here.
1639 if (Ptr->getType() != PointerTy)
1640 Ptr = IRB.CreateBitCast(Ptr, PointerTy, NamePrefix + "sroa_cast");
1641
1642 return Ptr;
1643}
1644
1645/// Compute the adjusted alignment for a load or store from an offset.
1646static unsigned getAdjustedAlignment(Instruction *I, uint64_t Offset,
1647 const DataLayout &DL) {
1648 unsigned Alignment;
1649 Type *Ty;
1650 if (auto *LI = dyn_cast<LoadInst>(I)) {
1651 Alignment = LI->getAlignment();
1652 Ty = LI->getType();
1653 } else if (auto *SI = dyn_cast<StoreInst>(I)) {
1654 Alignment = SI->getAlignment();
1655 Ty = SI->getValueOperand()->getType();
1656 } else {
1657 llvm_unreachable("Only loads and stores are allowed!");
1658 }
1659
1660 if (!Alignment)
1661 Alignment = DL.getABITypeAlignment(Ty);
1662
1663 return MinAlign(Alignment, Offset);
1664}
1665
1666/// Test whether we can convert a value from the old to the new type.
1667///
1668/// This predicate should be used to guard calls to convertValue in order to
1669/// ensure that we only try to convert viable values. The strategy is that we
1670/// will peel off single element struct and array wrappings to get to an
1671/// underlying value, and convert that value.
1672static bool canConvertValue(const DataLayout &DL, Type *OldTy, Type *NewTy) {
1673 if (OldTy == NewTy)
1674 return true;
1675
1676 // For integer types, we can't handle any bit-width differences. This would
1677 // break both vector conversions with extension and introduce endianness
1678 // issues when in conjunction with loads and stores.
1679 if (isa<IntegerType>(OldTy) && isa<IntegerType>(NewTy)) {
1680 assert(cast<IntegerType>(OldTy)->getBitWidth() !=
1681 cast<IntegerType>(NewTy)->getBitWidth() &&
1682 "We can't have the same bitwidth for different int types");
1683 return false;
1684 }
1685
1686 if (DL.getTypeSizeInBits(NewTy) != DL.getTypeSizeInBits(OldTy))
1687 return false;
1688 if (!NewTy->isSingleValueType() || !OldTy->isSingleValueType())
1689 return false;
1690
1691 // We can convert pointers to integers and vice-versa. Same for vectors
1692 // of pointers and integers.
1693 OldTy = OldTy->getScalarType();
1694 NewTy = NewTy->getScalarType();
1695 if (NewTy->isPointerTy() || OldTy->isPointerTy()) {
1696 if (NewTy->isPointerTy() && OldTy->isPointerTy()) {
1697 return cast<PointerType>(NewTy)->getPointerAddressSpace() ==
1698 cast<PointerType>(OldTy)->getPointerAddressSpace();
1699 }
1700
1701 // XXXAR: converting i8 addrspace(200) <-> i128/i256 also causes errors
1702 // TODO: Do we lose any important optimizations by skipping conversion?
1703
1704 // We can convert integers to integral pointers, but not to non-integral
1705 // pointers.
1706 if (OldTy->isIntegerTy()) {
1707 if (DL.isFatPointer(NewTy))
1708 return false;
1709 return !DL.isNonIntegralPointerType(NewTy);
1710 }
1711
1712 // We can convert integral pointers to integers, but non-integral pointers
1713 // need to remain pointers.
1714 if (!DL.isNonIntegralPointerType(OldTy)) {
1715 if (DL.isFatPointer(OldTy))
1716 return false;
1717 return NewTy->isIntegerTy();
1718 }
1719
1720 return false;
1721 }
1722
1723 return true;
1724}
1725
1726/// Generic routine to convert an SSA value to a value of a different
1727/// type.
1728///
1729/// This will try various different casting techniques, such as bitcasts,
1730/// inttoptr, and ptrtoint casts. Use the \c canConvertValue predicate to test
1731/// two types for viability with this routine.
1732static Value *convertValue(const DataLayout &DL, IRBuilderTy &IRB, Value *V,
1733 Type *NewTy) {
1734 Type *OldTy = V->getType();
1735 assert(canConvertValue(DL, OldTy, NewTy) && "Value not convertable to type");
1736
1737 if (OldTy == NewTy)
1738 return V;
1739
1740 assert(!(isa<IntegerType>(OldTy) && isa<IntegerType>(NewTy)) &&
1741 "Integer types must be the exact same to convert.");
1742
1743 // See if we need inttoptr for this type pair. A cast involving both scalars
1744 // and vectors requires and additional bitcast.
1745 if (OldTy->isIntOrIntVectorTy() && NewTy->isPtrOrPtrVectorTy()) {
1746 // Expand <2 x i32> to i8* --> <2 x i32> to i64 to i8*
1747 if (OldTy->isVectorTy() && !NewTy->isVectorTy())
1748 return IRB.CreateIntToPtr(IRB.CreateBitCast(V, DL.getIntPtrType(NewTy)),
1749 NewTy);
1750
1751 // Expand i128 to <2 x i8*> --> i128 to <2 x i64> to <2 x i8*>
1752 if (!OldTy->isVectorTy() && NewTy->isVectorTy())
1753 return IRB.CreateIntToPtr(IRB.CreateBitCast(V, DL.getIntPtrType(NewTy)),
1754 NewTy);
1755
1756 return IRB.CreateIntToPtr(V, NewTy);
1757 }
1758
1759 // See if we need ptrtoint for this type pair. A cast involving both scalars
1760 // and vectors requires and additional bitcast.
1761 if (OldTy->isPtrOrPtrVectorTy() && NewTy->isIntOrIntVectorTy()) {
1762 // Expand <2 x i8*> to i128 --> <2 x i8*> to <2 x i64> to i128
1763 if (OldTy->isVectorTy() && !NewTy->isVectorTy())
1764 return IRB.CreateBitCast(IRB.CreatePtrToInt(V, DL.getIntPtrType(OldTy)),
1765 NewTy);
1766
1767 // Expand i8* to <2 x i32> --> i8* to i64 to <2 x i32>
1768 if (!OldTy->isVectorTy() && NewTy->isVectorTy())
1769 return IRB.CreateBitCast(IRB.CreatePtrToInt(V, DL.getIntPtrType(OldTy)),
1770 NewTy);
1771
1772 return IRB.CreatePtrToInt(V, NewTy);
1773 }
1774
1775 return IRB.CreateBitCast(V, NewTy);
1776}
1777
1778/// Test whether the given slice use can be promoted to a vector.
1779///
1780/// This function is called to test each entry in a partition which is slated
1781/// for a single slice.
1782static bool isVectorPromotionViableForSlice(Partition &P, const Slice &S,
1783 VectorType *Ty,
1784 uint64_t ElementSize,
1785 const DataLayout &DL) {
1786 // First validate the slice offsets.
1787 uint64_t BeginOffset =
1788 std::max(S.beginOffset(), P.beginOffset()) - P.beginOffset();
1789 uint64_t BeginIndex = BeginOffset / ElementSize;
1790 if (BeginIndex * ElementSize != BeginOffset ||
1791 BeginIndex >= Ty->getNumElements())
1792 return false;
1793 uint64_t EndOffset =
1794 std::min(S.endOffset(), P.endOffset()) - P.beginOffset();
1795 uint64_t EndIndex = EndOffset / ElementSize;
1796 if (EndIndex * ElementSize != EndOffset || EndIndex > Ty->getNumElements())
1797 return false;
1798
1799 assert(EndIndex > BeginIndex && "Empty vector!");
1800 uint64_t NumElements = EndIndex - BeginIndex;
1801 Type *SliceTy = (NumElements == 1)
1802 ? Ty->getElementType()
1803 : VectorType::get(Ty->getElementType(), NumElements);
1804
1805 Type *SplitIntTy =
1806 Type::getIntNTy(Ty->getContext(), NumElements * ElementSize * 8);
1807
1808 Use *U = S.getUse();
1809
1810 if (MemIntrinsic *MI = dyn_cast<MemIntrinsic>(U->getUser())) {
1811 if (MI->isVolatile())
1812 return false;
1813 if (!S.isSplittable())
1814 return false; // Skip any unsplittable intrinsics.
1815 } else if (IntrinsicInst *II = dyn_cast<IntrinsicInst>(U->getUser())) {
1816 if (!II->isLifetimeStartOrEnd())
1817 return false;
1818 } else if (U->get()->getType()->getPointerElementType()->isStructTy()) {
1819 // Disable vector promotion when there are loads or stores of an FCA.
1820 return false;
1821 } else if (LoadInst *LI = dyn_cast<LoadInst>(U->getUser())) {
1822 if (LI->isVolatile())
1823 return false;
1824 Type *LTy = LI->getType();
1825 if (P.beginOffset() > S.beginOffset() || P.endOffset() < S.endOffset()) {
1826 assert(LTy->isIntegerTy());
1827 LTy = SplitIntTy;
1828 }
1829 if (!canConvertValue(DL, SliceTy, LTy))
1830 return false;
1831 } else if (StoreInst *SI = dyn_cast<StoreInst>(U->getUser())) {
1832 if (SI->isVolatile())
1833 return false;
1834 Type *STy = SI->getValueOperand()->getType();
1835 if (P.beginOffset() > S.beginOffset() || P.endOffset() < S.endOffset()) {
1836 assert(STy->isIntegerTy());
1837 STy = SplitIntTy;
1838 }
1839 if (!canConvertValue(DL, STy, SliceTy))
1840 return false;
1841 } else {
1842 return false;
1843 }
1844
1845 return true;
1846}
1847
1848/// Test whether the given alloca partitioning and range of slices can be
1849/// promoted to a vector.
1850///
1851/// This is a quick test to check whether we can rewrite a particular alloca
1852/// partition (and its newly formed alloca) into a vector alloca with only
1853/// whole-vector loads and stores such that it could be promoted to a vector
1854/// SSA value. We only can ensure this for a limited set of operations, and we
1855/// don't want to do the rewrites unless we are confident that the result will
1856/// be promotable, so we have an early test here.
1857static VectorType *isVectorPromotionViable(Partition &P, const DataLayout &DL) {
1858 // Collect the candidate types for vector-based promotion. Also track whether
1859 // we have different element types.
1860 SmallVector<VectorType *, 4> CandidateTys;
1861 Type *CommonEltTy = nullptr;
1862 bool HaveCommonEltTy = true;
1863 auto CheckCandidateType = [&](Type *Ty) {
1864 if (auto *VTy = dyn_cast<VectorType>(Ty)) {
1865 CandidateTys.push_back(VTy);
1866 if (!CommonEltTy)
1867 CommonEltTy = VTy->getElementType();
1868 else if (CommonEltTy != VTy->getElementType())
1869 HaveCommonEltTy = false;
1870 }
1871 };
1872 // Consider any loads or stores that are the exact size of the slice.
1873 for (const Slice &S : P)
1874 if (S.beginOffset() == P.beginOffset() &&
1875 S.endOffset() == P.endOffset()) {
1876 if (auto *LI = dyn_cast<LoadInst>(S.getUse()->getUser()))
1877 CheckCandidateType(LI->getType());
1878 else if (auto *SI = dyn_cast<StoreInst>(S.getUse()->getUser()))
1879 CheckCandidateType(SI->getValueOperand()->getType());
1880 }
1881
1882 // If we didn't find a vector type, nothing to do here.
1883 if (CandidateTys.empty())
1884 return nullptr;
1885
1886 // Remove non-integer vector types if we had multiple common element types.
1887 // FIXME: It'd be nice to replace them with integer vector types, but we can't
1888 // do that until all the backends are known to produce good code for all
1889 // integer vector types.
1890 if (!HaveCommonEltTy) {
1891 CandidateTys.erase(
1892 llvm::remove_if(CandidateTys,
1893 [](VectorType *VTy) {
1894 return !VTy->getElementType()->isIntegerTy();
1895 }),
1896 CandidateTys.end());
1897
1898 // If there were no integer vector types, give up.
1899 if (CandidateTys.empty())
1900 return nullptr;
1901
1902 // Rank the remaining candidate vector types. This is easy because we know
1903 // they're all integer vectors. We sort by ascending number of elements.
1904 auto RankVectorTypes = [&DL](VectorType *RHSTy, VectorType *LHSTy) {
1905 (void)DL;
1906 assert(DL.getTypeSizeInBits(RHSTy) == DL.getTypeSizeInBits(LHSTy) &&
1907 "Cannot have vector types of different sizes!");
1908 assert(RHSTy->getElementType()->isIntegerTy() &&
1909 "All non-integer types eliminated!");
1910 assert(LHSTy->getElementType()->isIntegerTy() &&
1911 "All non-integer types eliminated!");
1912 return RHSTy->getNumElements() < LHSTy->getNumElements();
1913 };
1914 llvm::sort(CandidateTys, RankVectorTypes);
1915 CandidateTys.erase(
1916 std::unique(CandidateTys.begin(), CandidateTys.end(), RankVectorTypes),
1917 CandidateTys.end());
1918 } else {
1919// The only way to have the same element type in every vector type is to
1920// have the same vector type. Check that and remove all but one.
1921#ifndef NDEBUG
1922 for (VectorType *VTy : CandidateTys) {
1923 assert(VTy->getElementType() == CommonEltTy &&
1924 "Unaccounted for element type!");
1925 assert(VTy == CandidateTys[0] &&
1926 "Different vector types with the same element type!");
1927 }
1928#endif
1929 CandidateTys.resize(1);
1930 }
1931
1932 // Try each vector type, and return the one which works.
1933 auto CheckVectorTypeForPromotion = [&](VectorType *VTy) {
1934 uint64_t ElementSize = DL.getTypeSizeInBits(VTy->getElementType());
1935
1936 // While the definition of LLVM vectors is bitpacked, we don't support sizes
1937 // that aren't byte sized.
1938 if (ElementSize % 8)
1939 return false;
1940 assert((DL.getTypeSizeInBits(VTy) % 8) == 0 &&
1941 "vector size not a multiple of element size?");
1942 ElementSize /= 8;
1943
1944 for (const Slice &S : P)
1945 if (!isVectorPromotionViableForSlice(P, S, VTy, ElementSize, DL))
1946 return false;
1947
1948 for (const Slice *S : P.splitSliceTails())
1949 if (!isVectorPromotionViableForSlice(P, *S, VTy, ElementSize, DL))
1950 return false;
1951
1952 return true;
1953 };
1954 for (VectorType *VTy : CandidateTys)
1955 if (CheckVectorTypeForPromotion(VTy))
1956 return VTy;
1957
1958 return nullptr;
1959}

1961/// Test whether a slice of an alloca is valid for integer widening.
1962///
1963/// This implements the necessary checking for the \c isIntegerWideningViable
1964/// test below on a single slice of the alloca.
1965static bool isIntegerWideningViableForSlice(const Slice &S,
1966 uint64_t AllocBeginOffset,
1967 Type *AllocaTy,
1968 const DataLayout &DL,
1969 bool &WholeAllocaOp) {
1970 uint64_t Size = DL.getTypeStoreSize(AllocaTy);
1971 if (Size*8 > DL.getLargestLegalIntTypeSizeInBits())
1972 return false;
1973
1974 uint64_t RelBegin = S.beginOffset() - AllocBeginOffset;
1975 uint64_t RelEnd = S.endOffset() - AllocBeginOffset;
1976
1977 // We can't reasonably handle cases where the load or store extends past
1978 // the end of the alloca's type and into its padding.
1979 if (RelEnd > Size)
1980 return false;
1981
1982 Use *U = S.getUse();
1983
1984 if (LoadInst *LI = dyn_cast<LoadInst>(U->getUser())) {
1985 if (LI->isVolatile())
1986 return false;
1987 // We can't handle loads that extend past the allocated memory.
1988 if (DL.getTypeStoreSize(LI->getType()) > Size)
1989 return false;
1990 // So far, AllocaSliceRewriter does not support widening split slice tails
1991 // in rewriteIntegerLoad.
1992 if (S.beginOffset() < AllocBeginOffset)
1993 return false;
1994 // Note that we don't count vector loads or stores as whole-alloca
1995 // operations which enable integer widening because we would prefer to use
1996 // vector widening instead.
1997 if (!isa<VectorType>(LI->getType()) && RelBegin == 0 && RelEnd == Size)
1998 WholeAllocaOp = true;
1999 if (IntegerType *ITy = dyn_cast<IntegerType>(LI->getType())) {
2000 if (ITy->getBitWidth() < DL.getTypeStoreSizeInBits(ITy))
2001 return false;
2002 } else if (RelBegin != 0 || RelEnd != Size ||
2003 !canConvertValue(DL, AllocaTy, LI->getType())) {
2004 // Non-integer loads need to be convertible from the alloca type so that
2005 // they are promotable.
2006 return false;
2007 }
2008 } else if (StoreInst *SI = dyn_cast<StoreInst>(U->getUser())) {
2009 Type *ValueTy = SI->getValueOperand()->getType();
2010 if (SI->isVolatile())
2011 return false;
2012 // We can't handle stores that extend past the allocated memory.
2013 if (DL.getTypeStoreSize(ValueTy) > Size)
2014 return false;
2015 // So far, AllocaSliceRewriter does not support widening split slice tails
2016 // in rewriteIntegerStore.
2017 if (S.beginOffset() < AllocBeginOffset)
2018 return false;
2019 // Note that we don't count vector loads or stores as whole-alloca
2020 // operations which enable integer widening because we would prefer to use
2021 // vector widening instead.
2022 if (!isa<VectorType>(ValueTy) && RelBegin == 0 && RelEnd == Size)
2023 WholeAllocaOp = true;
2024 if (IntegerType *ITy = dyn_cast<IntegerType>(ValueTy)) {
2025 if (ITy->getBitWidth() < DL.getTypeStoreSizeInBits(ITy))
2026 return false;
2027 } else if (RelBegin != 0 || RelEnd != Size ||
2028 !canConvertValue(DL, ValueTy, AllocaTy)) {
2029 // Non-integer stores need to be convertible to the alloca type so that
2030 // they are promotable.
2031 return false;
2032 }
2033 } else if (MemIntrinsic *MI = dyn_cast<MemIntrinsic>(U->getUser())) {
2034 if (MI->isVolatile() || !isa<Constant>(MI->getLength()))
2035 return false;
2036 if (!S.isSplittable())
2037 return false; // Skip any unsplittable intrinsics.
2038 } else if (IntrinsicInst *II = dyn_cast<IntrinsicInst>(U->getUser())) {
2039 if (!II->isLifetimeStartOrEnd())
2040 return false;
2041 } else {
2042 return false;
2043 }
2044
2045 return true;
2046}
2047
2048/// Test whether the given alloca partition's integer operations can be
2049/// widened to promotable ones.
2050///
2051/// This is a quick test to check whether we can rewrite the integer loads and
2052/// stores to a particular alloca into wider loads and stores and be able to
2053/// promote the resulting alloca.
2054static bool isIntegerWideningViable(Partition &P, Type *AllocaTy,
2055 const DataLayout &DL) {
2056 uint64_t SizeInBits = DL.getTypeSizeInBits(AllocaTy);
2057 // Don't create integer types larger than the maximum bitwidth.
2058 if (SizeInBits > IntegerType::MAX_INT_BITS)
2059 return false;
2060 if (AllocaTy->isPointerTy() &&
2061 SizeInBits*8 > DL.getLargestLegalIntTypeSizeInBits())
2062 return false;
2063
2064
2065 // Don't try to handle allocas with bit-padding.
2066 if (SizeInBits != DL.getTypeStoreSizeInBits(AllocaTy))
2067 return false;
2068
2069 // We need to ensure that an integer type with the appropriate bitwidth can
2070 // be converted to the alloca type, whatever that is. We don't want to force
2071 // the alloca itself to have an integer type if there is a more suitable one.
2072 Type *IntTy = Type::getIntNTy(AllocaTy->getContext(), SizeInBits);
2073 if (!canConvertValue(DL, AllocaTy, IntTy) ||
2074 !canConvertValue(DL, IntTy, AllocaTy))
2075 return false;
2076
2077 // While examining uses, we ensure that the alloca has a covering load or
2078 // store. We don't want to widen the integer operations only to fail to
2079 // promote due to some other unsplittable entry (which we may make splittable
2080 // later). However, if there are only splittable uses, go ahead and assume
2081 // that we cover the alloca.
2082 // FIXME: We shouldn't consider split slices that happen to start in the
2083 // partition here...
2084 bool WholeAllocaOp =
2085 P.begin() != P.end() ? false : DL.isLegalInteger(SizeInBits);
2086
2087 for (const Slice &S : P)
2088 if (!isIntegerWideningViableForSlice(S, P.beginOffset(), AllocaTy, DL,
2089 WholeAllocaOp))
2090 return false;
2091
2092 for (const Slice *S : P.splitSliceTails())
2093 if (!isIntegerWideningViableForSlice(*S, P.beginOffset(), AllocaTy, DL,
2094 WholeAllocaOp))
2095 return false;
2096
2097 return WholeAllocaOp;
2098}

2100static Value *extractInteger(const DataLayout &DL, IRBuilderTy &IRB, Value *V,
2101 IntegerType *Ty, uint64_t Offset,
2102 const Twine &Name) {
2103 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << " start: " << *V << "\n");
2104 IntegerType *IntTy = cast<IntegerType>(V->getType());
2105 assert(DL.getTypeStoreSize(Ty) + Offset <= DL.getTypeStoreSize(IntTy) &&
2106 "Element extends past full value");
2107 uint64_t ShAmt = 8 * Offset;
2108 if (DL.isBigEndian())
2109 ShAmt = 8 * (DL.getTypeStoreSize(IntTy) - DL.getTypeStoreSize(Ty) - Offset);
2110 if (ShAmt) {
2111 V = IRB.CreateLShr(V, ShAmt, Name + ".shift");
2112 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << " shifted: " << *V << "\n");
2113 }
2114 assert(Ty->getBitWidth() <= IntTy->getBitWidth() &&
2115 "Cannot extract to a larger integer!");
2116 if (Ty != IntTy) {
2117 V = IRB.CreateTrunc(V, Ty, Name + ".trunc");
2118 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << " trunced: " << *V << "\n");
2119 }
2120 return V;
2121}
2122
2123static Value *insertInteger(const DataLayout &DL, IRBuilderTy &IRB, Value *Old,
2124 Value *V, uint64_t Offset, const Twine &Name) {
2125 IntegerType *IntTy = cast<IntegerType>(Old->getType());
2126 IntegerType *Ty = cast<IntegerType>(V->getType());
2127 assert(Ty->getBitWidth() <= IntTy->getBitWidth() &&
2128 "Cannot insert a larger integer!");
2129 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << " start: " << *V << "\n");
2130 if (Ty != IntTy) {
2131 V = IRB.CreateZExt(V, IntTy, Name + ".ext");
2132 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << " extended: " << *V << "\n");
2133 }
2134 assert(DL.getTypeStoreSize(Ty) + Offset <= DL.getTypeStoreSize(IntTy) &&
2135 "Element store outside of alloca store");
2136 uint64_t ShAmt = 8 * Offset;
2137 if (DL.isBigEndian())
2138 ShAmt = 8 * (DL.getTypeStoreSize(IntTy) - DL.getTypeStoreSize(Ty) - Offset);
2139 if (ShAmt) {
2140 V = IRB.CreateShl(V, ShAmt, Name + ".shift");
2141 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << " shifted: " << *V << "\n");
2142 }
2143
2144 if (ShAmt || Ty->getBitWidth() < IntTy->getBitWidth()) {
2145 APInt Mask = ~Ty->getMask().zext(IntTy->getBitWidth()).shl(ShAmt);
2146 Old = IRB.CreateAnd(Old, Mask, Name + ".mask");
2147 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << " masked: " << *Old << "\n");
2148 V = IRB.CreateOr(Old, V, Name + ".insert");
2149 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << " inserted: " << *V << "\n");
2150 }
2151 return V;
2152}
2153
2154static Value *extractVector(IRBuilderTy &IRB, Value *V, unsigned BeginIndex,
2155 unsigned EndIndex, const Twine &Name) {
2156 VectorType *VecTy = cast<VectorType>(V->getType());
2157 unsigned NumElements = EndIndex - BeginIndex;
2158 assert(NumElements <= VecTy->getNumElements() && "Too many elements!");
2159
2160 if (NumElements == VecTy->getNumElements())
2161 return V;
2162
2163 if (NumElements == 1) {
2164 V = IRB.CreateExtractElement(V, IRB.getInt32(BeginIndex),
2165 Name + ".extract");
2166 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << " extract: " << *V << "\n");
2167 return V;
2168 }
2169
2170 SmallVector<Constant *, 8> Mask;
2171 Mask.reserve(NumElements);
2172 for (unsigned i = BeginIndex; i != EndIndex; ++i)
2173 Mask.push_back(IRB.getInt32(i));
2174 V = IRB.CreateShuffleVector(V, UndefValue::get(V->getType()),
2175 ConstantVector::get(Mask), Name + ".extract");
2176 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << " shuffle: " << *V << "\n");
2177 return V;
2178}
2179
2180static Value *insertVector(IRBuilderTy &IRB, Value *Old, Value *V,
2181 unsigned BeginIndex, const Twine &Name) {
2182 VectorType *VecTy = cast<VectorType>(Old->getType());
2183 assert(VecTy && "Can only insert a vector into a vector");
2184
2185 VectorType *Ty = dyn_cast<VectorType>(V->getType());
2186 if (!Ty) {
2187 // Single element to insert.
2188 V = IRB.CreateInsertElement(Old, V, IRB.getInt32(BeginIndex),
2189 Name + ".insert");
2190 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << " insert: " << *V << "\n");
2191 return V;
2192 }
2193
2194 assert(Ty->getNumElements() <= VecTy->getNumElements() &&
2195 "Too many elements!");
2196 if (Ty->getNumElements() == VecTy->getNumElements()) {
2197 assert(V->getType() == VecTy && "Vector type mismatch");
2198 return V;
2199 }
2200 unsigned EndIndex = BeginIndex + Ty->getNumElements();
2201
2202 // When inserting a smaller vector into the larger to store, we first
2203 // use a shuffle vector to widen it with undef elements, and then
2204 // a second shuffle vector to select between the loaded vector and the
2205 // incoming vector.
2206 SmallVector<Constant *, 8> Mask;
2207 Mask.reserve(VecTy->getNumElements());
2208 for (unsigned i = 0; i != VecTy->getNumElements(); ++i)
2209 if (i >= BeginIndex && i < EndIndex)
2210 Mask.push_back(IRB.getInt32(i - BeginIndex));
2211 else
2212 Mask.push_back(UndefValue::get(IRB.getInt32Ty()));
2213 V = IRB.CreateShuffleVector(V, UndefValue::get(V->getType()),
2214 ConstantVector::get(Mask), Name + ".expand");
2215 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << " shuffle: " << *V << "\n");
2216
2217 Mask.clear();
2218 for (unsigned i = 0; i != VecTy->getNumElements(); ++i)
2219 Mask.push_back(IRB.getInt1(i >= BeginIndex && i < EndIndex));
2220
2221 V = IRB.CreateSelect(ConstantVector::get(Mask), V, Old, Name + "blend");
2222
2223 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << " blend: " << *V << "\n");
2224 return V;
2225}
