3443/// Strip aggregate type wrapping.
3444///
3445/// This removes no-op aggregate types wrapping an underlying type. It will
3446/// strip as many layers of types as it can without changing either the type
3447/// size or the allocated size.
3448static Type *stripAggregateTypeWrapping(const DataLayout &DL, Type *Ty) {
3449 if (Ty->isSingleValueType())
3450 return Ty;
3451
3452 uint64_t AllocSize = DL.getTypeAllocSize(Ty);
3453 uint64_t TypeSize = DL.getTypeSizeInBits(Ty);
3454
3455 Type *InnerTy;
3456 if (ArrayType *ArrTy = dyn_cast<ArrayType>(Ty)) {
3457 InnerTy = ArrTy->getElementType();
3458 } else if (StructType *STy = dyn_cast<StructType>(Ty)) {
3459 const StructLayout *SL = DL.getStructLayout(STy);
3460 unsigned Index = SL->getElementContainingOffset(0);
3461 InnerTy = STy->getElementType(Index);
3462 } else {
3463 return Ty;
3464 }
3465
3466 if (AllocSize > DL.getTypeAllocSize(InnerTy) ||
3467 TypeSize > DL.getTypeSizeInBits(InnerTy))
3468 return Ty;
3469
3470 return stripAggregateTypeWrapping(DL, InnerTy);
3471}
3472
3473/// Try to find a partition of the aggregate type passed in for a given
3474/// offset and size.
3475///
3476/// This recurses through the aggregate type and tries to compute a subtype
3477/// based on the offset and size. When the offset and size span a sub-section
3478/// of an array, it will even compute a new array type for that sub-section,
3479/// and the same for structs.
3480///
3481/// Note that this routine is very strict and tries to find a partition of the
3482/// type which produces the *exact* right offset and size. It is not forgiving
3483/// when the size or offset cause either end of type-based partition to be off.
3484/// Also, this is a best-effort routine. It is reasonable to give up and not
3485/// return a type if necessary.
3486static Type *getTypePartition(const DataLayout &DL, Type *Ty, uint64_t Offset,
3487 uint64_t Size) {
3488 if (Offset == 0 && DL.getTypeAllocSize(Ty) == Size)
3489 return stripAggregateTypeWrapping(DL, Ty);
3490 if (Offset > DL.getTypeAllocSize(Ty) ||
3491 (DL.getTypeAllocSize(Ty) - Offset) < Size)
3492 return nullptr;
3493
3494 if (SequentialType *SeqTy = dyn_cast<SequentialType>(Ty)) {
3495 Type *ElementTy = SeqTy->getElementType();
3496 uint64_t ElementSize = DL.getTypeAllocSize(ElementTy);
3497 uint64_t NumSkippedElements = Offset / ElementSize;
3498 if (NumSkippedElements >= SeqTy->getNumElements())
3499 return nullptr;
3500 Offset -= NumSkippedElements * ElementSize;
3501
3502 // First check if we need to recurse.
3503 if (Offset > 0 || Size < ElementSize) {
3504 // Bail if the partition ends in a different array element.
3505 if ((Offset + Size) > ElementSize)
3506 return nullptr;
3507 // Recurse through the element type trying to peel off offset bytes.
3508 return getTypePartition(DL, ElementTy, Offset, Size);
3509 }
3510 assert(Offset == 0);
3511
3512 if (Size == ElementSize)
3513 return stripAggregateTypeWrapping(DL, ElementTy);
3514 assert(Size > ElementSize);
3515 uint64_t NumElements = Size / ElementSize;
3516 if (NumElements * ElementSize != Size)
3517 return nullptr;
3518 return ArrayType::get(ElementTy, NumElements);
3519 }
3520
3521 StructType *STy = dyn_cast<StructType>(Ty);
3522 if (!STy)
3523 return nullptr;
3524
3525 const StructLayout *SL = DL.getStructLayout(STy);
3526 if (Offset >= SL->getSizeInBytes())
3527 return nullptr;
3528 uint64_t EndOffset = Offset + Size;
3529 if (EndOffset > SL->getSizeInBytes())
3530 return nullptr;
3531
3532 unsigned Index = SL->getElementContainingOffset(Offset);
3533 Offset -= SL->getElementOffset(Index);
3534
3535 Type *ElementTy = STy->getElementType(Index);
3536 uint64_t ElementSize = DL.getTypeAllocSize(ElementTy);
3537 if (Offset >= ElementSize)
3538 return nullptr; // The offset points into alignment padding.
3539
3540 // See if any partition must be contained by the element.
3541 if (Offset > 0 || Size < ElementSize) {
3542 if ((Offset + Size) > ElementSize)
3543 return nullptr;
3544 return getTypePartition(DL, ElementTy, Offset, Size);
3545 }
3546 assert(Offset == 0);
3547
3548 if (Size == ElementSize)
3549 return stripAggregateTypeWrapping(DL, ElementTy);
3550
3551 StructType::element_iterator EI = STy->element_begin() + Index,
3552 EE = STy->element_end();
3553 if (EndOffset < SL->getSizeInBytes()) {
3554 unsigned EndIndex = SL->getElementContainingOffset(EndOffset);
3555 if (Index == EndIndex)
3556 return nullptr; // Within a single element and its padding.
3557
3558 // Don't try to form "natural" types if the elements don't line up with the
3559 // expected size.
3560 // FIXME: We could potentially recurse down through the last element in the
3561 // sub-struct to find a natural end point.
3562 if (SL->getElementOffset(EndIndex) != EndOffset)
3563 return nullptr;
3564
3565 assert(Index < EndIndex);
3566 EE = STy->element_begin() + EndIndex;
3567 }
3568
3569 // Try to build up a sub-structure.
3570 StructType *SubTy =
3571 StructType::get(STy->getContext(), makeArrayRef(EI, EE), STy->isPacked());
3572 const StructLayout *SubSL = DL.getStructLayout(SubTy);
3573 if (Size != SubSL->getSizeInBytes())
3574 return nullptr; // The sub-struct doesn't have quite the size needed.
3575
3576 return SubTy;
3577}
3578
3579/// Pre-split loads and stores to simplify rewriting.
3580///
3581/// We want to break up the splittable load+store pairs as much as
3582/// possible. This is important to do as a preprocessing step, as once we
3583/// start rewriting the accesses to partitions of the alloca we lose the
3584/// necessary information to correctly split apart paired loads and stores
3585/// which both point into this alloca. The case to consider is something like
3586/// the following:
3587///
3588/// %a = alloca [12 x i8]
3589/// %gep1 = getelementptr [12 x i8]* %a, i32 0, i32 0
3590/// %gep2 = getelementptr [12 x i8]* %a, i32 0, i32 4
3591/// %gep3 = getelementptr [12 x i8]* %a, i32 0, i32 8
3592/// %iptr1 = bitcast i8* %gep1 to i64*
3593/// %iptr2 = bitcast i8* %gep2 to i64*
3594/// %fptr1 = bitcast i8* %gep1 to float*
3595/// %fptr2 = bitcast i8* %gep2 to float*
3596/// %fptr3 = bitcast i8* %gep3 to float*
3597/// store float 0.0, float* %fptr1
3598/// store float 1.0, float* %fptr2
3599/// %v = load i64* %iptr1
3600/// store i64 %v, i64* %iptr2
3601/// %f1 = load float* %fptr2
3602/// %f2 = load float* %fptr3
3603///
3604/// Here we want to form 3 partitions of the alloca, each 4 bytes large, and
3605/// promote everything so we recover the 2 SSA values that should have been
3606/// there all along.
3607///
3608/// \returns true if any changes are made.
3609bool SROA::presplitLoadsAndStores(AllocaInst &AI, AllocaSlices &AS) {
3610 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << "Pre-splitting loads and stores\n");
3611
3612 // Track the loads and stores which are candidates for pre-splitting here, in
3613 // the order they first appear during the partition scan. These give stable
3614 // iteration order and a basis for tracking which loads and stores we
3615 // actually split.
3616 SmallVector<LoadInst *, 4> Loads;
3617 SmallVector<StoreInst *, 4> Stores;
3618
3619 // We need to accumulate the splits required of each load or store where we
3620 // can find them via a direct lookup. This is important to cross-check loads
3621 // and stores against each other. We also track the slice so that we can kill
3622 // all the slices that end up split.
3623 struct SplitOffsets {
3624 Slice *S;
3625 std::vector<uint64_t> Splits;
3626 };
3627 SmallDenseMap<Instruction *, SplitOffsets, 8> SplitOffsetsMap;
3628
3629 // Track loads out of this alloca which cannot, for any reason, be pre-split.
3630 // This is important as we also cannot pre-split stores of those loads!
3631 // FIXME: This is all pretty gross. It means that we can be more aggressive
3632 // in pre-splitting when the load feeding the store happens to come from
3633 // a separate alloca. Put another way, the effectiveness of SROA would be
3634 // decreased by a frontend which just concatenated all of its local allocas
3635 // into one big flat alloca. But defeating such patterns is exactly the job
3636 // SROA is tasked with! Sadly, to not have this discrepancy we would have
3637 // change store pre-splitting to actually force pre-splitting of the load
3638 // that feeds it *and all stores*. That makes pre-splitting much harder, but
3639 // maybe it would make it more principled?
3640 SmallPtrSet<LoadInst *, 8> UnsplittableLoads;
3641
3642 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << " Searching for candidate loads and stores\n");
3643 for (auto &P : AS.partitions()) {
3644 for (Slice &S : P) {
3645 Instruction *I = cast<Instruction>(S.getUse()->getUser());
3646 if (!S.isSplittable() || S.endOffset() <= P.endOffset()) {
3647 // If this is a load we have to track that it can't participate in any
3648 // pre-splitting. If this is a store of a load we have to track that
3649 // that load also can't participate in any pre-splitting.
3650 if (auto *LI = dyn_cast<LoadInst>(I))
3651 UnsplittableLoads.insert(LI);
3652 else if (auto *SI = dyn_cast<StoreInst>(I))
3653 if (auto *LI = dyn_cast<LoadInst>(SI->getValueOperand()))
3654 UnsplittableLoads.insert(LI);
3655 continue;
3656 }
3657 assert(P.endOffset() > S.beginOffset() &&
3658 "Empty or backwards partition!");
3659
3660 // Determine if this is a pre-splittable slice.
3661 if (auto *LI = dyn_cast<LoadInst>(I)) {
3662 assert(!LI->isVolatile() && "Cannot split volatile loads!");
3663
3664 // The load must be used exclusively to store into other pointers for
3665 // us to be able to arbitrarily pre-split it. The stores must also be
3666 // simple to avoid changing semantics.
3667 auto IsLoadSimplyStored = [](LoadInst *LI) {
3668 for (User *LU : LI->users()) {
3669 auto *SI = dyn_cast<StoreInst>(LU);
3670 if (!SI || !SI->isSimple())
3671 return false;
3672 }
3673 return true;
3674 };
3675 if (!IsLoadSimplyStored(LI)) {
3676 UnsplittableLoads.insert(LI);
3677 continue;
3678 }
3679
3680 Loads.push_back(LI);
3681 } else if (auto *SI = dyn_cast<StoreInst>(I)) {
3682 if (S.getUse() != &SI->getOperandUse(SI->getPointerOperandIndex()))
3683 // Skip stores *of* pointers. FIXME: This shouldn't even be possible!
3684 continue;
3685 auto *StoredLoad = dyn_cast<LoadInst>(SI->getValueOperand());
3686 if (!StoredLoad || !StoredLoad->isSimple())
3687 continue;
3688 assert(!SI->isVolatile() && "Cannot split volatile stores!");
3689
3690 Stores.push_back(SI);
3691 } else {
3692 // Other uses cannot be pre-split.
3693 continue;
3694 }
3695
3696 // Record the initial split.
3697 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << " Candidate: " << *I << "\n");
3698 auto &Offsets = SplitOffsetsMap[I];
3699 assert(Offsets.Splits.empty() &&
3700 "Should not have splits the first time we see an instruction!");
3701 Offsets.S = &S;
3702 Offsets.Splits.push_back(P.endOffset() - S.beginOffset());
3703 }
3704
3705 // Now scan the already split slices, and add a split for any of them which
3706 // we're going to pre-split.
3707 for (Slice *S : P.splitSliceTails()) {
3708 auto SplitOffsetsMapI =
3709 SplitOffsetsMap.find(cast<Instruction>(S->getUse()->getUser()));
3710 if (SplitOffsetsMapI == SplitOffsetsMap.end())
3711 continue;
3712 auto &Offsets = SplitOffsetsMapI->second;
3713
3714 assert(Offsets.S == S && "Found a mismatched slice!");
3715 assert(!Offsets.Splits.empty() &&
3716 "Cannot have an empty set of splits on the second partition!");
3717 assert(Offsets.Splits.back() ==
3718 P.beginOffset() - Offsets.S->beginOffset() &&
3719 "Previous split does not end where this one begins!");
3720
3721 // Record each split. The last partition's end isn't needed as the size
3722 // of the slice dictates that.
3723 if (S->endOffset() > P.endOffset())
3724 Offsets.Splits.push_back(P.endOffset() - Offsets.S->beginOffset());
3725 }
3726 }
3727
3728 // We may have split loads where some of their stores are split stores. For
3729 // such loads and stores, we can only pre-split them if their splits exactly
3730 // match relative to their starting offset. We have to verify this prior to
3731 // any rewriting.
3732 Stores.erase(
3733 llvm::remove_if(Stores,
3734 [&UnsplittableLoads, &SplitOffsetsMap](StoreInst *SI) {
3735 // Lookup the load we are storing in our map of split
3736 // offsets.
3737 auto *LI = cast<LoadInst>(SI->getValueOperand());
3738 // If it was completely unsplittable, then we're done,
3739 // and this store can't be pre-split.
3740 if (UnsplittableLoads.count(LI))
3741 return true;
3742
3743 auto LoadOffsetsI = SplitOffsetsMap.find(LI);
3744 if (LoadOffsetsI == SplitOffsetsMap.end())
3745 return false; // Unrelated loads are definitely safe.
3746 auto &LoadOffsets = LoadOffsetsI->second;
3747
3748 // Now lookup the store's offsets.
3749 auto &StoreOffsets = SplitOffsetsMap[SI];
3750
3751 // If the relative offsets of each split in the load and
3752 // store match exactly, then we can split them and we
3753 // don't need to remove them here.
3754 if (LoadOffsets.Splits == StoreOffsets.Splits)
3755 return false;
3756
3757 LLVM_DEBUG(
3758 dbgs()
3759 << " Mismatched splits for load and store:\n"
3760 << " " << *LI << "\n"
3761 << " " << *SI << "\n");
3762
3763 // We've found a store and load that we need to split
3764 // with mismatched relative splits. Just give up on them
3765 // and remove both instructions from our list of
3766 // candidates.
3767 UnsplittableLoads.insert(LI);
3768 return true;
3769 }),
3770 Stores.end());
3771 // Now we have to go *back* through all the stores, because a later store may
3772 // have caused an earlier store's load to become unsplittable and if it is
3773 // unsplittable for the later store, then we can't rely on it being split in
3774 // the earlier store either.
3775 Stores.erase(llvm::remove_if(Stores,
3776 [&UnsplittableLoads](StoreInst *SI) {
3777 auto *LI =
3778 cast<LoadInst>(SI->getValueOperand());
3779 return UnsplittableLoads.count(LI);
3780 }),
3781 Stores.end());
3782 // Once we've established all the loads that can't be split for some reason,
3783 // filter any that made it into our list out.
3784 Loads.erase(llvm::remove_if(Loads,
3785 [&UnsplittableLoads](LoadInst *LI) {
3786 return UnsplittableLoads.count(LI);
3787 }),
3788 Loads.end());
3789
3790 // If no loads or stores are left, there is no pre-splitting to be done for
3791 // this alloca.
3792 if (Loads.empty() && Stores.empty())
3793 return false;
3794
3795 // From here on, we can't fail and will be building new accesses, so rig up
3796 // an IR builder.
3797 IRBuilderTy IRB(&AI);
3798
3799 // Collect the new slices which we will merge into the alloca slices.
3800 SmallVector<Slice, 4> NewSlices;
3801
3802 // Track any allocas we end up splitting loads and stores for so we iterate
3803 // on them.
3804 SmallPtrSet<AllocaInst *, 4> ResplitPromotableAllocas;
3805
3806 // At this point, we have collected all of the loads and stores we can
3807 // pre-split, and the specific splits needed for them. We actually do the
3808 // splitting in a specific order in order to handle when one of the loads in
3809 // the value operand to one of the stores.
3810 //
3811 // First, we rewrite all of the split loads, and just accumulate each split
3812 // load in a parallel structure. We also build the slices for them and append
3813 // them to the alloca slices.
3814 SmallDenseMap<LoadInst *, std::vector<LoadInst *>, 1> SplitLoadsMap;
3815 std::vector<LoadInst *> SplitLoads;
3816 const DataLayout &DL = AI.getModule()->getDataLayout();
3817 for (LoadInst *LI : Loads) {
3818 SplitLoads.clear();
3819
3820 IntegerType *Ty = cast<IntegerType>(LI->getType());
3821 uint64_t LoadSize = Ty->getBitWidth() / 8;
3822 assert(LoadSize > 0 && "Cannot have a zero-sized integer load!");
3823
3824 auto &Offsets = SplitOffsetsMap[LI];
3825 assert(LoadSize == Offsets.S->endOffset() - Offsets.S->beginOffset() &&
3826 "Slice size should always match load size exactly!");
3827 uint64_t BaseOffset = Offsets.S->beginOffset();
3828 assert(BaseOffset + LoadSize > BaseOffset &&
3829 "Cannot represent alloca access size using 64-bit integers!");
3830
3831 Instruction *BasePtr = cast<Instruction>(LI->getPointerOperand());
3832 IRB.SetInsertPoint(LI);
3833
3834 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << " Splitting load: " << *LI << "\n");
3835
3836 uint64_t PartOffset = 0, PartSize = Offsets.Splits.front();
3837 int Idx = 0, Size = Offsets.Splits.size();
3838 for (;;) {
3839 auto *PartTy = Type::getIntNTy(Ty->getContext(), PartSize * 8);
3840 auto AS = LI->getPointerAddressSpace();
3841 auto *PartPtrTy = PartTy->getPointerTo(AS);
3842 LoadInst *PLoad = IRB.CreateAlignedLoad(
3843 PartTy,
3844 getAdjustedPtr(IRB, DL, BasePtr,
3845 APInt(DL.getIndexSizeInBits(AS), PartOffset),
3846 PartPtrTy, BasePtr->getName() + "."),
3847 getAdjustedAlignment(LI, PartOffset, DL), /*IsVolatile*/ false,
3848 LI->getName());
3849 PLoad->copyMetadata(*LI, {LLVMContext::MD_mem_parallel_loop_access,
3850 LLVMContext::MD_access_group});
3851
3852 // Append this load onto the list of split loads so we can find it later
3853 // to rewrite the stores.
3854 SplitLoads.push_back(PLoad);
3855
3856 // Now build a new slice for the alloca.
3857 NewSlices.push_back(
3858 Slice(BaseOffset + PartOffset, BaseOffset + PartOffset + PartSize,
3859 &PLoad->getOperandUse(PLoad->getPointerOperandIndex()),
3860 /*IsSplittable*/ false));
3861 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << " new slice [" << NewSlices.back().beginOffset()
3862 << ", " << NewSlices.back().endOffset()
3863 << "): " << *PLoad << "\n");
3864
3865 // See if we've handled all the splits.
3866 if (Idx >= Size)
3867 break;
3868
3869 // Setup the next partition.
3870 PartOffset = Offsets.Splits[Idx];
3871 ++Idx;
3872 PartSize = (Idx < Size ? Offsets.Splits[Idx] : LoadSize) - PartOffset;
3873 }
3874
3875 // Now that we have the split loads, do the slow walk over all uses of the
3876 // load and rewrite them as split stores, or save the split loads to use
3877 // below if the store is going to be split there anyways.
3878 bool DeferredStores = false;
3879 for (User *LU : LI->users()) {
3880 StoreInst *SI = cast<StoreInst>(LU);
3881 if (!Stores.empty() && SplitOffsetsMap.count(SI)) {
3882 DeferredStores = true;
3883 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << " Deferred splitting of store: " << *SI
3884 << "\n");
3885 continue;
3886 }
3887
3888 Value *StoreBasePtr = SI->getPointerOperand();
3889 IRB.SetInsertPoint(SI);
3890
3891 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << " Splitting store of load: " << *SI << "\n");
3892
3893 for (int Idx = 0, Size = SplitLoads.size(); Idx < Size; ++Idx) {
3894 LoadInst *PLoad = SplitLoads[Idx];
3895 uint64_t PartOffset = Idx == 0 ? 0 : Offsets.Splits[Idx - 1];
3896 auto *PartPtrTy =
3897 PLoad->getType()->getPointerTo(SI->getPointerAddressSpace());
3898
3899 auto AS = SI->getPointerAddressSpace();
3900 StoreInst *PStore = IRB.CreateAlignedStore(
3901 PLoad,
3902 getAdjustedPtr(IRB, DL, StoreBasePtr,
3903 APInt(DL.getIndexSizeInBits(AS), PartOffset),
3904 PartPtrTy, StoreBasePtr->getName() + "."),
3905 getAdjustedAlignment(SI, PartOffset, DL), /*IsVolatile*/ false);
3906 PStore->copyMetadata(*LI, {LLVMContext::MD_mem_parallel_loop_access,
3907 LLVMContext::MD_access_group});
3908 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << " +" << PartOffset << ":" << *PStore << "\n");
3909 }
3910
3911 // We want to immediately iterate on any allocas impacted by splitting
3912 // this store, and we have to track any promotable alloca (indicated by
3913 // a direct store) as needing to be resplit because it is no longer
3914 // promotable.
3915 if (AllocaInst *OtherAI = dyn_cast<AllocaInst>(StoreBasePtr)) {
3916 ResplitPromotableAllocas.insert(OtherAI);
3917 Worklist.insert(OtherAI);
3918 } else if (AllocaInst *OtherAI = dyn_cast<AllocaInst>(
3919 StoreBasePtr->stripInBoundsOffsets())) {
3920 Worklist.insert(OtherAI);
3921 }
3922
3923 // Mark the original store as dead.
3924 DeadInsts.insert(SI);
3925 }
3926
3927 // Save the split loads if there are deferred stores among the users.
3928 if (DeferredStores)
3929 SplitLoadsMap.insert(std::make_pair(LI, std::move(SplitLoads)));
3930
3931 // Mark the original load as dead and kill the original slice.
3932 DeadInsts.insert(LI);
3933 Offsets.S->kill();
3934 }
3935
3936 // Second, we rewrite all of the split stores. At this point, we know that
3937 // all loads from this alloca have been split already. For stores of such
3938 // loads, we can simply look up the pre-existing split loads. For stores of
3939 // other loads, we split those loads first and then write split stores of
3940 // them.
3941 for (StoreInst *SI : Stores) {
3942 auto *LI = cast<LoadInst>(SI->getValueOperand());
3943 IntegerType *Ty = cast<IntegerType>(LI->getType());
3944 uint64_t StoreSize = Ty->getBitWidth() / 8;
3945 assert(StoreSize > 0 && "Cannot have a zero-sized integer store!");
3946
3947 auto &Offsets = SplitOffsetsMap[SI];
3948 assert(StoreSize == Offsets.S->endOffset() - Offsets.S->beginOffset() &&
3949 "Slice size should always match load size exactly!");
3950 uint64_t BaseOffset = Offsets.S->beginOffset();
3951 assert(BaseOffset + StoreSize > BaseOffset &&
3952 "Cannot represent alloca access size using 64-bit integers!");
3953
3954 Value *LoadBasePtr = LI->getPointerOperand();
3955 Instruction *StoreBasePtr = cast<Instruction>(SI->getPointerOperand());
3956
3957 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << " Splitting store: " << *SI << "\n");
3958
3959 // Check whether we have an already split load.
3960 auto SplitLoadsMapI = SplitLoadsMap.find(LI);
3961 std::vector<LoadInst *> *SplitLoads = nullptr;
3962 if (SplitLoadsMapI != SplitLoadsMap.end()) {
3963 SplitLoads = &SplitLoadsMapI->second;
3964 assert(SplitLoads->size() == Offsets.Splits.size() + 1 &&
3965 "Too few split loads for the number of splits in the store!");
3966 } else {
3967 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << " of load: " << *LI << "\n");
3968 }
3969
3970 uint64_t PartOffset = 0, PartSize = Offsets.Splits.front();
3971 int Idx = 0, Size = Offsets.Splits.size();
3972 for (;;) {
3973 auto *PartTy = Type::getIntNTy(Ty->getContext(), PartSize * 8);
3974 auto *LoadPartPtrTy = PartTy->getPointerTo(LI->getPointerAddressSpace());
3975 auto *StorePartPtrTy = PartTy->getPointerTo(SI->getPointerAddressSpace());
3976
3977 // Either lookup a split load or create one.
3978 LoadInst *PLoad;
3979 if (SplitLoads) {
3980 PLoad = (*SplitLoads)[Idx];
3981 } else {
3982 IRB.SetInsertPoint(LI);
3983 auto AS = LI->getPointerAddressSpace();
3984 PLoad = IRB.CreateAlignedLoad(
3985 PartTy,
3986 getAdjustedPtr(IRB, DL, LoadBasePtr,
3987 APInt(DL.getIndexSizeInBits(AS), PartOffset),
3988 LoadPartPtrTy, LoadBasePtr->getName() + "."),
3989 getAdjustedAlignment(LI, PartOffset, DL), /*IsVolatile*/ false,
3990 LI->getName());
3991 }
3992
3993 // And store this partition.
3994 IRB.SetInsertPoint(SI);
3995 auto AS = SI->getPointerAddressSpace();
3996 StoreInst *PStore = IRB.CreateAlignedStore(
3997 PLoad,
3998 getAdjustedPtr(IRB, DL, StoreBasePtr,
3999 APInt(DL.getIndexSizeInBits(AS), PartOffset),
4000 StorePartPtrTy, StoreBasePtr->getName() + "."),
4001 getAdjustedAlignment(SI, PartOffset, DL), /*IsVolatile*/ false);
4002
4003 // Now build a new slice for the alloca.
4004 NewSlices.push_back(
4005 Slice(BaseOffset + PartOffset, BaseOffset + PartOffset + PartSize,
4006 &PStore->getOperandUse(PStore->getPointerOperandIndex()),
4007 /*IsSplittable*/ false));
4008 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << " new slice [" << NewSlices.back().beginOffset()
4009 << ", " << NewSlices.back().endOffset()
4010 << "): " << *PStore << "\n");
4011 if (!SplitLoads) {
4012 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << " of split load: " << *PLoad << "\n");
4013 }
4014
4015 // See if we've finished all the splits.
4016 if (Idx >= Size)
4017 break;
4018
4019 // Setup the next partition.
4020 PartOffset = Offsets.Splits[Idx];
4021 ++Idx;
4022 PartSize = (Idx < Size ? Offsets.Splits[Idx] : StoreSize) - PartOffset;
4023 }
4024
4025 // We want to immediately iterate on any allocas impacted by splitting
4026 // this load, which is only relevant if it isn't a load of this alloca and
4027 // thus we didn't already split the loads above. We also have to keep track
4028 // of any promotable allocas we split loads on as they can no longer be
4029 // promoted.
4030 if (!SplitLoads) {
4031 if (AllocaInst *OtherAI = dyn_cast<AllocaInst>(LoadBasePtr)) {
4032 assert(OtherAI != &AI && "We can't re-split our own alloca!");
4033 ResplitPromotableAllocas.insert(OtherAI);
4034 Worklist.insert(OtherAI);
4035 } else if (AllocaInst *OtherAI = dyn_cast<AllocaInst>(
4036 LoadBasePtr->stripInBoundsOffsets())) {
4037 assert(OtherAI != &AI && "We can't re-split our own alloca!");
4038 Worklist.insert(OtherAI);
4039 }
4040 }
4041
4042 // Mark the original store as dead now that we've split it up and kill its
4043 // slice. Note that we leave the original load in place unless this store
4044 // was its only use. It may in turn be split up if it is an alloca load
4045 // for some other alloca, but it may be a normal load. This may introduce
4046 // redundant loads, but where those can be merged the rest of the optimizer
4047 // should handle the merging, and this uncovers SSA splits which is more
4048 // important. In practice, the original loads will almost always be fully
4049 // split and removed eventually, and the splits will be merged by any
4050 // trivial CSE, including instcombine.
4051 if (LI->hasOneUse()) {
4052 assert(*LI->user_begin() == SI && "Single use isn't this store!");
4053 DeadInsts.insert(LI);
4054 }
4055 DeadInsts.insert(SI);
4056 Offsets.S->kill();
4057 }
4058
4059 // Remove the killed slices that have ben pre-split.
4060 AS.erase(llvm::remove_if(AS, [](const Slice &S) { return S.isDead(); }),
4061 AS.end());
4062
4063 // Insert our new slices. This will sort and merge them into the sorted
4064 // sequence.
4065 AS.insert(NewSlices);
4066
4067 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << " Pre-split slices:\n");
4068#ifndef NDEBUG
4069 for (auto I = AS.begin(), E = AS.end(); I != E; ++I)
4070 LLVM_DEBUG(AS.print(dbgs(), I, " "));
4071#endif
4072
4073 // Finally, don't try to promote any allocas that new require re-splitting.
4074 // They have already been added to the worklist above.
4075 PromotableAllocas.erase(
4076 llvm::remove_if(
4077 PromotableAllocas,
4078 [&](AllocaInst *AI) { return ResplitPromotableAllocas.count(AI); }),
4079 PromotableAllocas.end());
4080
4081 return true;
4082}
4083
4084/// Rewrite an alloca partition's users.
4085///
4086/// This routine drives both of the rewriting goals of the SROA pass. It tries
4087/// to rewrite uses of an alloca partition to be conducive for SSA value
4088/// promotion. If the partition needs a new, more refined alloca, this will
4089/// build that new alloca, preserving as much type information as possible, and
4090/// rewrite the uses of the old alloca to point at the new one and have the
4091/// appropriate new offsets. It also evaluates how successful the rewrite was
4092/// at enabling promotion and if it was successful queues the alloca to be
4093/// promoted.
4094AllocaInst *SROA::rewritePartition(AllocaInst &AI, AllocaSlices &AS,
4095 Partition &P) {
4096 // Try to compute a friendly type for this partition of the alloca. This
4097 // won't always succeed, in which case we fall back to a legal integer type
4098 // or an i8 array of an appropriate size.
4099 Type *SliceTy = nullptr;
4100 const DataLayout &DL = AI.getModule()->getDataLayout();
4101 if (Type *CommonUseTy = findCommonType(P.begin(), P.end(), P.endOffset()))
4102 if (DL.getTypeAllocSize(CommonUseTy) >= P.size())
4103 SliceTy = CommonUseTy;
4104 if (!SliceTy)
4105 if (Type *TypePartitionTy = getTypePartition(DL, AI.getAllocatedType(),
4106 P.beginOffset(), P.size()))
4107 SliceTy = TypePartitionTy;
4108 if ((!SliceTy || (SliceTy->isArrayTy() &&
4109 SliceTy->getArrayElementType()->isIntegerTy())) &&
4110 DL.isLegalInteger(P.size() * 8))
4111 SliceTy = Type::getIntNTy(*C, P.size() * 8);
4112 if (!SliceTy)
4113 SliceTy = ArrayType::get(Type::getInt8Ty(*C), P.size());
4114 assert(DL.getTypeAllocSize(SliceTy) >= P.size());
4115
4116 bool IsIntegerPromotable = isIntegerWideningViable(P, SliceTy, DL);
4117
4118 VectorType *VecTy =
4119 IsIntegerPromotable ? nullptr : isVectorPromotionViable(P, DL);
4120 if (VecTy)
4121 SliceTy = VecTy;
4122
4123 // Check for the case where we're going to rewrite to a new alloca of the
4124 // exact same type as the original, and with the same access offsets. In that
4125 // case, re-use the existing alloca, but still run through the rewriter to
4126 // perform phi and select speculation.
4127 // P.beginOffset() can be non-zero even with the same type in a case with
4128 // out-of-bounds access (e.g. @PR35657 function in SROA/basictest.ll).
4129 AllocaInst *NewAI;
4130 if (SliceTy == AI.getAllocatedType() && P.beginOffset() == 0) {
4131 NewAI = &AI;
4132 // FIXME: We should be able to bail at this point with "nothing changed".
4133 // FIXME: We might want to defer PHI speculation until after here.
4134 // FIXME: return nullptr;
4135 } else {
4136 unsigned Alignment = AI.getAlignment();
4137 if (!Alignment) {
4138 // The minimum alignment which users can rely on when the explicit
4139 // alignment is omitted or zero is that required by the ABI for this
4140 // type.
4141 Alignment = DL.getABITypeAlignment(AI.getAllocatedType());
4142 }
4143 Alignment = MinAlign(Alignment, P.beginOffset());
4144 // If we will get at least this much alignment from the type alone, leave
4145 // the alloca's alignment unconstrained.
4146 if (Alignment <= DL.getABITypeAlignment(SliceTy))
4147 Alignment = 0;
4148 NewAI = new AllocaInst(
4149 SliceTy, AI.getType()->getAddressSpace(), nullptr, Alignment,
4150 AI.getName() + ".sroa." + Twine(P.begin() - AS.begin()), &AI);
4151 // Copy the old AI debug location over to the new one.
4152 NewAI->setDebugLoc(AI.getDebugLoc());
4153 ++NumNewAllocas;
4154 }
4155
4156 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << "Rewriting alloca partition "
4157 << "[" << P.beginOffset() << "," << P.endOffset()
4158 << ") to: " << *NewAI << "\n");
4159
4160 // Track the high watermark on the worklist as it is only relevant for
4161 // promoted allocas. We will reset it to this point if the alloca is not in
4162 // fact scheduled for promotion.
4163 unsigned PPWOldSize = PostPromotionWorklist.size();
4164 unsigned NumUses = 0;
4165 SmallSetVector<PHINode *, 8> PHIUsers;
4166 SmallSetVector<SelectInst *, 8> SelectUsers;
4167
4168 AllocaSliceRewriter Rewriter(DL, AS, *this, AI, *NewAI, P.beginOffset(),
4169 P.endOffset(), IsIntegerPromotable, VecTy,
4170 PHIUsers, SelectUsers);
4171 bool Promotable = true;
4172 for (Slice *S : P.splitSliceTails()) {
4173 Promotable &= Rewriter.visit(S);
4174 ++NumUses;
4175 }
4176 for (Slice &S : P) {
4177 Promotable &= Rewriter.visit(&S);
4178 ++NumUses;
4179 }
4180
4181 NumAllocaPartitionUses += NumUses;
4182 MaxUsesPerAllocaPartition.updateMax(NumUses);
4183
4184 // Now that we've processed all the slices in the new partition, check if any
4185 // PHIs or Selects would block promotion.
4186 for (PHINode *PHI : PHIUsers)
4187 if (!isSafePHIToSpeculate(*PHI)) {
4188 Promotable = false;
4189 PHIUsers.clear();
4190 SelectUsers.clear();
4191 break;
4192 }
4193
4194 for (SelectInst *Sel : SelectUsers)
4195 if (!isSafeSelectToSpeculate(*Sel)) {
4196 Promotable = false;
4197 PHIUsers.clear();
4198 SelectUsers.clear();
4199 break;
4200 }
4201
4202 if (Promotable) {
4203 if (PHIUsers.empty() && SelectUsers.empty()) {
4204 // Promote the alloca.
4205 PromotableAllocas.push_back(NewAI);
4206 } else {
4207 // If we have either PHIs or Selects to speculate, add them to those
4208 // worklists and re-queue the new alloca so that we promote in on the
4209 // next iteration.
4210 for (PHINode *PHIUser : PHIUsers)
4211 SpeculatablePHIs.insert(PHIUser);
4212 for (SelectInst *SelectUser : SelectUsers)
4213 SpeculatableSelects.insert(SelectUser);
4214 Worklist.insert(NewAI);
4215 }
4216 } else {
4217 // Drop any post-promotion work items if promotion didn't happen.
4218 while (PostPromotionWorklist.size() > PPWOldSize)
4219 PostPromotionWorklist.pop_back();
4220
4221 // We couldn't promote and we didn't create a new partition, nothing
4222 // happened.
4223 if (NewAI == &AI)
4224 return nullptr;
4225
4226 // If we can't promote the alloca, iterate on it to check for new
4227 // refinements exposed by splitting the current alloca. Don't iterate on an
4228 // alloca which didn't actually change and didn't get promoted.
4229 Worklist.insert(NewAI);
4230 }
4231
4232 return NewAI;
4233}
4234
4235/// Walks the slices of an alloca and form partitions based on them,
4236/// rewriting each of their uses.
4237bool SROA::splitAlloca(AllocaInst &AI, AllocaSlices &AS) {
4238 if (AS.begin() == AS.end())
4239 return false;
4240
4241 unsigned NumPartitions = 0;
4242 bool Changed = false;
4243 const DataLayout &DL = AI.getModule()->getDataLayout();
4244
4245 // First try to pre-split loads and stores.
4246 Changed |= presplitLoadsAndStores(AI, AS);
4247
4248 // Now that we have identified any pre-splitting opportunities,
4249 // mark loads and stores unsplittable except for the following case.
4250 // We leave a slice splittable if all other slices are disjoint or fully
4251 // included in the slice, such as whole-alloca loads and stores.
4252 // If we fail to split these during pre-splitting, we want to force them
4253 // to be rewritten into a partition.
4254 bool IsSorted = true;
4255
4256 uint64_t AllocaSize = DL.getTypeAllocSize(AI.getAllocatedType());
4257 const uint64_t MaxBitVectorSize = 1024;
4258 if (AllocaSize <= MaxBitVectorSize) {
4259 // If a byte boundary is included in any load or store, a slice starting or
4260 // ending at the boundary is not splittable.
4261 SmallBitVector SplittableOffset(AllocaSize + 1, true);
4262 for (Slice &S : AS)
4263 for (unsigned O = S.beginOffset() + 1;
4264 O < S.endOffset() && O < AllocaSize; O++)
4265 SplittableOffset.reset(O);
4266
4267 for (Slice &S : AS) {
4268 if (!S.isSplittable())
4269 continue;
4270
4271 if ((S.beginOffset() > AllocaSize || SplittableOffset[S.beginOffset()]) &&
4272 (S.endOffset() > AllocaSize || SplittableOffset[S.endOffset()]))
4273 continue;
4274
4275 if (isa<LoadInst>(S.getUse()->getUser()) ||
4276 isa<StoreInst>(S.getUse()->getUser())) {
4277 S.makeUnsplittable();
4278 IsSorted = false;
4279 }
4280 }
4281 }
4282 else {
4283 // We only allow whole-alloca splittable loads and stores
4284 // for a large alloca to avoid creating too large BitVector.
4285 for (Slice &S : AS) {
4286 if (!S.isSplittable())
4287 continue;
4288
4289 if (S.beginOffset() == 0 && S.endOffset() >= AllocaSize)
4290 continue;
4291
4292 if (isa<LoadInst>(S.getUse()->getUser()) ||
4293 isa<StoreInst>(S.getUse()->getUser())) {
4294 S.makeUnsplittable();
4295 IsSorted = false;
4296 }
4297 }
4298 }
4299
4300 if (!IsSorted)
4301 llvm::sort(AS);
4302
4303 /// Describes the allocas introduced by rewritePartition in order to migrate
4304 /// the debug info.
4305 struct Fragment {
4306 AllocaInst *Alloca;
4307 uint64_t Offset;
4308 uint64_t Size;
4309 Fragment(AllocaInst *AI, uint64_t O, uint64_t S)
4310 : Alloca(AI), Offset(O), Size(S) {}
4311 };
4312 SmallVector<Fragment, 4> Fragments;
4313
4314 // Rewrite each partition.
4315 for (auto &P : AS.partitions()) {
4316 if (AllocaInst *NewAI = rewritePartition(AI, AS, P)) {
4317 Changed = true;
4318 if (NewAI != &AI) {
4319 uint64_t SizeOfByte = 8;
4320 uint64_t AllocaSize = DL.getTypeSizeInBits(NewAI->getAllocatedType());
4321 // Don't include any padding.
4322 uint64_t Size = std::min(AllocaSize, P.size() * SizeOfByte);
4323 Fragments.push_back(Fragment(NewAI, P.beginOffset() * SizeOfByte, Size));
4324 }
4325 }
4326 ++NumPartitions;
4327 }
4328
4329 NumAllocaPartitions += NumPartitions;
4330 MaxPartitionsPerAlloca.updateMax(NumPartitions);
4331
4332 // Migrate debug information from the old alloca to the new alloca(s)
4333 // and the individual partitions.
4334 TinyPtrVector<DbgVariableIntrinsic *> DbgDeclares = FindDbgAddrUses(&AI);
4335 if (!DbgDeclares.empty()) {
4336 auto *Var = DbgDeclares.front()->getVariable();
4337 auto *Expr = DbgDeclares.front()->getExpression();
4338 auto VarSize = Var->getSizeInBits();
4339 DIBuilder DIB(*AI.getModule(), /*AllowUnresolved*/ false);
4340 uint64_t AllocaSize = DL.getTypeSizeInBits(AI.getAllocatedType());
4341 for (auto Fragment : Fragments) {
4342 // Create a fragment expression describing the new partition or reuse AI's
4343 // expression if there is only one partition.
4344 auto *FragmentExpr = Expr;
4345 if (Fragment.Size < AllocaSize || Expr->isFragment()) {
4346 // If this alloca is already a scalar replacement of a larger aggregate,
4347 // Fragment.Offset describes the offset inside the scalar.
4348 auto ExprFragment = Expr->getFragmentInfo();
4349 uint64_t Offset = ExprFragment ? ExprFragment->OffsetInBits : 0;
4350 uint64_t Start = Offset + Fragment.Offset;
4351 uint64_t Size = Fragment.Size;
4352 if (ExprFragment) {
4353 uint64_t AbsEnd =
4354 ExprFragment->OffsetInBits + ExprFragment->SizeInBits;
4355 if (Start >= AbsEnd)
4356 // No need to describe a SROAed padding.
4357 continue;
4358 Size = std::min(Size, AbsEnd - Start);
4359 }
4360 // The new, smaller fragment is stenciled out from the old fragment.
4361 if (auto OrigFragment = FragmentExpr->getFragmentInfo()) {
4362 assert(Start >= OrigFragment->OffsetInBits &&
4363 "new fragment is outside of original fragment");
4364 Start -= OrigFragment->OffsetInBits;
4365 }
4366
4367 // The alloca may be larger than the variable.
4368 if (VarSize) {
4369 if (Size > *VarSize)
4370 Size = *VarSize;
4371 if (Size == 0 || Start + Size > *VarSize)
4372 continue;
4373 }
4374
4375 // Avoid creating a fragment expression that covers the entire variable.
4376 if (!VarSize || *VarSize != Size) {
4377 if (auto E =
4378 DIExpression::createFragmentExpression(Expr, Start, Size))
4379 FragmentExpr = *E;
4380 else
4381 continue;
4382 }
4383 }
4384
4385 // Remove any existing intrinsics describing the same alloca.
4386 for (DbgVariableIntrinsic *OldDII : FindDbgAddrUses(Fragment.Alloca))
4387 OldDII->eraseFromParent();
4388
4389 DIB.insertDeclare(Fragment.Alloca, Var, FragmentExpr,
4390 DbgDeclares.front()->getDebugLoc(), &AI);
4391 }
4392 }
4393 return Changed;
4394}

4396/// Clobber a use with undef, deleting the used value if it becomes dead.
4397void SROA::clobberUse(Use &U) {
4398 Value *OldV = U;
4399 // Replace the use with an undef value.
4400 U = UndefValue::get(OldV->getType());
4401
4402 // Check for this making an instruction dead. We have to garbage collect
4403 // all the dead instructions to ensure the uses of any alloca end up being
4404 // minimal.
4405 if (Instruction *OldI = dyn_cast<Instruction>(OldV))
4406 if (isInstructionTriviallyDead(OldI)) {
4407 DeadInsts.insert(OldI);
4408 }
4409}
4410
4411/// Analyze an alloca for SROA.
4412///
4413/// This analyzes the alloca to ensure we can reason about it, builds
4414/// the slices of the alloca, and then hands it off to be split and
4415/// rewritten as needed.
4416bool SROA::runOnAlloca(AllocaInst &AI) {
4417 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << "SROA alloca: " << AI << "\n");
4418 ++NumAllocasAnalyzed;
4419
4420 // Special case dead allocas, as they're trivial.
4421 if (AI.use_empty()) {
4422 AI.eraseFromParent();
4423 return true;
4424 }
4425 const DataLayout &DL = AI.getModule()->getDataLayout();
4426
4427 // Skip alloca forms that this analysis can't handle.
4428 if (AI.isArrayAllocation() || !AI.getAllocatedType()->isSized() ||
4429 DL.getTypeAllocSize(AI.getAllocatedType()) == 0)
4430 return false;
4431
4432 bool Changed = false;
4433
4434 // First, split any FCA loads and stores touching this alloca to promote
4435 // better splitting and promotion opportunities.
4436 AggLoadStoreRewriter AggRewriter(DL);
4437 Changed |= AggRewriter.rewrite(AI);
4438
4439 // Build the slices using a recursive instruction-visiting builder.
4440 AllocaSlices AS(DL, AI);
4441 LLVM_DEBUG(AS.print(dbgs()));
4442 if (AS.isEscaped())
4443 return Changed;
4444
4445 // Delete all the dead users of this alloca before splitting and rewriting it.
4446 for (Instruction *DeadUser : AS.getDeadUsers()) {
4447 // Free up everything used by this instruction.
4448 for (Use &DeadOp : DeadUser->operands())
4449 clobberUse(DeadOp);
4450
4451 // Now replace the uses of this instruction.
4452 DeadUser->replaceAllUsesWith(UndefValue::get(DeadUser->getType()));
4453
4454 // And mark it for deletion.
4455 DeadInsts.insert(DeadUser);
4456 Changed = true;
4457 }
4458 for (Use *DeadOp : AS.getDeadOperands()) {
4459 clobberUse(*DeadOp);
4460 Changed = true;
4461 }
4462
4463 // No slices to split. Leave the dead alloca for a later pass to clean up.
4464 if (AS.begin() == AS.end())
4465 return Changed;
4466
4467 Changed |= splitAlloca(AI, AS);
4468
4469 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << " Speculating PHIs\n");
4470 while (!SpeculatablePHIs.empty())
4471 speculatePHINodeLoads(*SpeculatablePHIs.pop_back_val());
4472
4473 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << " Speculating Selects\n");
4474 while (!SpeculatableSelects.empty())
4475 speculateSelectInstLoads(*SpeculatableSelects.pop_back_val());
4476
4477 return Changed;
4478}
4479
4480/// Delete the dead instructions accumulated in this run.
4481///
4482/// Recursively deletes the dead instructions we've accumulated. This is done
4483/// at the very end to maximize locality of the recursive delete and to
4484/// minimize the problems of invalidated instruction pointers as such pointers
4485/// are used heavily in the intermediate stages of the algorithm.
4486///
4487/// We also record the alloca instructions deleted here so that they aren't
4488/// subsequently handed to mem2reg to promote.
4489bool SROA::deleteDeadInstructions(
4490 SmallPtrSetImpl<AllocaInst *> &DeletedAllocas) {
4491 bool Changed = false;
4492 while (!DeadInsts.empty()) {
4493 Instruction *I = DeadInsts.pop_back_val();
4494 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << "Deleting dead instruction: " << *I << "\n");
4495
4496 // If the instruction is an alloca, find the possible dbg.declare connected
4497 // to it, and remove it too. We must do this before calling RAUW or we will
4498 // not be able to find it.
4499 if (AllocaInst *AI = dyn_cast<AllocaInst>(I)) {
4500 DeletedAllocas.insert(AI);
4501 for (DbgVariableIntrinsic *OldDII : FindDbgAddrUses(AI))
4502 OldDII->eraseFromParent();
4503 }
4504
4505 I->replaceAllUsesWith(UndefValue::get(I->getType()));
4506
4507 for (Use &Operand : I->operands())
4508 if (Instruction *U = dyn_cast<Instruction>(Operand)) {
4509 // Zero out the operand and see if it becomes trivially dead.
4510 Operand = nullptr;
4511 if (isInstructionTriviallyDead(U))
4512 DeadInsts.insert(U);
4513 }
4514
4515 ++NumDeleted;
4516 I->eraseFromParent();
4517 Changed = true;
4518 }
4519 return Changed;
4520}
4521
4522/// Promote the allocas, using the best available technique.
4523///
4524/// This attempts to promote whatever allocas have been identified as viable in
4525/// the PromotableAllocas list. If that list is empty, there is nothing to do.
4526/// This function returns whether any promotion occurred.
4527bool SROA::promoteAllocas(Function &F) {
4528 if (PromotableAllocas.empty())
4529 return false;
4530
4531 NumPromoted += PromotableAllocas.size();
4532
4533 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << "Promoting allocas with mem2reg...\n");
4534 PromoteMemToReg(PromotableAllocas, *DT, AC);
4535 PromotableAllocas.clear();
4536 return true;
4537}
4538
4539PreservedAnalyses SROA::runImpl(Function &F, DominatorTree &RunDT,
4540 AssumptionCache &RunAC) {
4541 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << "SROA function: " << F.getName() << "\n");
4542 C = &F.getContext();
4543 DT = &RunDT;
4544 AC = &RunAC;
4545
4546 BasicBlock &EntryBB = F.getEntryBlock();
4547 for (BasicBlock::iterator I = EntryBB.begin(), E = std::prev(EntryBB.end());
4548 I != E; ++I) {
4549 if (AllocaInst *AI = dyn_cast<AllocaInst>(I))
4550 Worklist.insert(AI);
4551 }
4552
4553 bool Changed = false;
4554 // A set of deleted alloca instruction pointers which should be removed from
4555 // the list of promotable allocas.
4556 SmallPtrSet<AllocaInst *, 4> DeletedAllocas;
4557
4558 do {
4559 while (!Worklist.empty()) {
4560 Changed |= runOnAlloca(*Worklist.pop_back_val());
4561 Changed |= deleteDeadInstructions(DeletedAllocas);
4562
4563 // Remove the deleted allocas from various lists so that we don't try to
4564 // continue processing them.
4565 if (!DeletedAllocas.empty()) {
4566 auto IsInSet = [&](AllocaInst *AI) { return DeletedAllocas.count(AI); };
4567 Worklist.remove_if(IsInSet);
4568 PostPromotionWorklist.remove_if(IsInSet);
4569 PromotableAllocas.erase(llvm::remove_if(PromotableAllocas, IsInSet),
4570 PromotableAllocas.end());
4571 DeletedAllocas.clear();
4572 }
4573 }
4574
4575 Changed |= promoteAllocas(F);
4576
4577 Worklist = PostPromotionWorklist;
4578 PostPromotionWorklist.clear();
4579 } while (!Worklist.empty());
4580
4581 if (!Changed)
4582 return PreservedAnalyses::all();
4583
4584 PreservedAnalyses PA;
4585 PA.preserveSet<CFGAnalyses>();
4586 PA.preserve<GlobalsAA>();
4587 return PA;
4588}
4589
4590PreservedAnalyses SROA::run(Function &F, FunctionAnalysisManager &AM) {
4591 return runImpl(F, AM.getResult<DominatorTreeAnalysis>(F),
4592 AM.getResult<AssumptionAnalysis>(F));
4593}
